<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>Take notice that the Canada Revenue Agency hereby appeals to the Court of Appeal for British Columbia from the order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Punnett of the Supreme Court of British Columbia, pronounced the 2<SUP>nd</SUP> day of March, 2018, at Victoria, British Columbia.</P>
<P>1. The appeal is from a:
<P1>[X] Trial Judgment</P1>
<P1>[ ] Summary Trial Judgment</P1>
<P1>[ ] Order of a Statutory Body</P1>
<P1>[ ] Chambers Judgment</P1></P>
<P>2. If the appeal is from an appeal under Rule 18-3 or 23-6(8) of the Supreme Court Civil Rules or Rule 18-3 or 22-7(8) of the Supreme Court Family Rules, name the maker of the original decision, direction or order:</P>
<P>3. Please identify which of the following is involved in the appeal:
<P1>[ ] Constitutional/Administrative</P1>
<P1>[ ] Civil Procedure</P1>
<P1>[ ] Commercial</P1>
<P1>Family&mdash;</P1>
<P1>[ ] Divorce</P1>
<P1>[ ] <EM>Family Law Act</EM></P1>
<P1>[ ] Corollary Relief in a Divorce Proceeding</P1>
<P1>[ ] Other Family</P1>
<P1>[ ] Motor Vehicle Accidents</P1>
<P1>[ ] Municipal Law</P1>
<P1>[ ] Real Property</P1>
<P1>[X] Torts</P1>
<P1>[ ] Equity</P1>
<P1>[ ] Wills and Estates</P1></P>
<P>(The Divorce Registry will, as applicable, be notified by the Court of Appeal Registry on filing if the appeal involves divorce, corollary relief in divorce proceeding or matters under the <EM>Family Relations Act</EM>)</P>
<P>And further take notice that the Court of Appeal will be moved at the hearing of this appeal for an order that:
<P1>1. the order of March 2, 2018 be set aside;</P1>
<P1>2. the Appellant be awarded its costs in this Court and the Court below; and</P1>
<P1>3. such other relief as this Court considers appropriate.</P1></P>
<P>The grounds for the appeal are:
<P1>1. The trial judge erred in law in reversing the onus of proof by requiring the appellant to prove the material facts in the malicious prosecution case; the issue is not whether the material facts were proved during the malicious prosecution case, but whether they could amount to proof of reasonable and probable cause for the Crown to commence a criminal prosecution;</P1>
<P1>2. The trial judge erred in law in finding that the Crown was required to prove the actual mechanics of fraud in order to establish the <EM>actus reus</EM> of tax evasion at the criminal trial;</P1>
<P1>3. The trial judge erred in fact and law in finding that the material facts known to the Crown could not establish reasonable and probable cause for prosecution;</P1>
<P1>4. The trial judge erred in law and fact in finding that the CRA initiated the prosecution;</P1>
<P1>5. The trial judge made a palpable and overriding error of fact in finding that the CRA investigator suppressed or withheld material evidence from the Crown, and that he was motivated by malice;</P1>
<P1>6. The trial judge made a palpable and overriding error in awarding the legal costs of the defence of the plaintiffs' corporations in the criminal trial, when the corporations were not plaintiffs in the civil trial; and</P1>
<P1>7. Such other grounds as the Appellant may submit at the hearing of this matter.</P1></P>
<P>The trial of this proceeding occupied twelve (12) days.</P>
<P>Dated at Vancouver, British Columbia, this 3<SUP>rd</SUP> day of April, 2018.</P>
