<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>&ldquo;Reasonable and probable cause&rdquo; under the third element of the test for malicious prosecution in <EM>Miazga</EM> requires a prosecutor to objectively assess the legal strength of the case. Probable guilt means that the prosecutor believes, based on an existing state of circumstances, proof beyond a reasonable doubt could be made out in a court of law. Where private action is taken against a Crown attorney for malicious prosecution, the trial judge must decide whether, on the basis of the circumstances known to the prosecutor at the relevant time, reasonable and probable cause existed to commence or continue a prosecution from an objective standpoint. The Crown defendant is not required to prove that the criminal allegations are in fact made out.</P>
<P>These fundamental propositions have been ignored in this case. The trial judge reversed the onus of proof by requiring the defendants to prove that the criminal allegations of tax evasion were true. Moreover, the trial judge erroneously held that the elements of tax evasion required the defendants to prove the actual mechanics of the fraudulent scheme. This in turn led him to conclude that the CRA investigator had intentionally suppressed or withheld material information from the Crown because he was motivated by malice, contrary to the evidence before the court.</P>
<P>The trial was fundamentally flawed as a consequence of the trial judge's misapprehension of the law which then corrupted his analysis of the evidence. The Respondents neither proved an absence of reasonable and probable cause nor did they prove that the CRA investigator held any improper purpose in the course of his investigation. As a result, there was no basis in law or on the facts of this case for a finding of malicious prosecution.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>The CRA Investigation and Referral For Charge Approval</TI>
<P>1. On March 3, 2006, the Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;) contacted the Respondents to begin an audit of their restaurant business, MGM Restaurant Ltd. (&ldquo;MGM&rdquo;). An anonymous informant had reported to the CRA that MGM had unreported cash sales and paid suppliers in cash.
<P1>Appeal Book (&ldquo;AB&rdquo;) p. 332, para. 5; p. 333, para. 8: <EM>Witness Report of Glen Foster</EM></P1></P>
<P>2. The Respondents had destroyed their records, including till tapes and other source documents. However, the auditor Glen Foster, was able to conduct an audit based on a review of records in the Respondents' accountant's office. He found that large amounts of cash which could not be explained by the reported sales of the businesses had been deposited into the Respondents' accounts prior to the audit. There were also increases in reported cash sales after the audit without corresponding expenses. Based on these and other findings, the auditor referred the case to the CRA's Special Investigations section to consider a criminal investigation.
<P1>AB p. 532: <EM>Audit Referral to Special Investigations</EM></P1></P>
<P>3. A Primary Report was prepared recommending investigation. A full criminal investigation was launched. Searches under warrant took place in January of 2007. During the search the Respondents' bookkeeper Deborah Ferens, told CRA investigator Terry Finlay, that she only worked from daily sales summary sheets provided to her by Mr. Samaroo; she did not look at till tapes.
<P1>AB p. 3&ndash;15: <EM>Primary Report</EM>; p. 16&ndash;26: <EM>Terry Findlay Notes of Ferens Interview</EM></P1></P>
<P>4. Following the searches the investigation file was transferred to Investigator Keith Kendal. Mr. Kendal prepared a draft prosecution report in December of 2007. The report was reviewed by Janna Hyman, Senior Counsel in the Public Prosecution Service of Canada (&ldquo;PPSC&rdquo;) Economic Crimes Group, who then assigned the file to Counsel Lisa McLean in January of 2008 for a preliminary consideration of whether a prosecution should proceed.
<P1>Transcript Volume (&ldquo;Ts. V.&rdquo;) 2, p. 327, line 29&ndash;41, <EM>Kendal</EM>; AB p. 27&ndash;54: <EM>Draft Prosecution Report</EM>; Ts. V. 2, p. 559, l. 29 to p. 560, l. 33<EM>, Hyman</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>5. Ms. McLean prepared a working memo concluding that a prosecution was justified on the evidence against Tony Samaroo personally and as a party to the corporate offences of MGM. However, the available evidence against Helen Samaroo and another corporation, Samaroo Holdings Limited (&ldquo;SHL&rdquo;) at that time did not meet the Federal Prosecution Deskbook standard for laying charges. Ms. McLean determined that further steps in the investigation needed to occur before charges could be laid.
<P1>Ts. V. 1, p. 146, l. 31&mdash;p. 148, l. 28: <EM>McLean</EM>; AB p. 58&ndash;67: <EM>Draft Charge Approval Memo</EM></P1></P>
<P>6. Brian Jones was appointed as agent of the Director of Public Prosecutions regarding charges against the Respondents for offences under sections 239(1)(a) and (d) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> and under the <EM>Excise Tax Act</EM>, for the taxation years 2004 to 2006 by way of a retainer letter dated January 22, 2008.
<P1>AB p. 68-69: <EM>Letter of Appointment</EM></P1></P>
<P>7. Ms. Hyman became the supervising PPSC counsel for the prosecution. She communicated regularly with Mr. Jones. She reviewed the materials from the CRA including a finalized prosecution report with attachments dated March 18, 2008 (the &ldquo;Prosecution Report&rdquo;). In her opinion the evidence justified prosecution of both Respondents as well as MGM and SHL.
<P1>Ts. V. 2, p. 564, l. 7- to p. 565, l. 7; p. 572, l. 11&ndash;33: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 611, l. 23&mdash;p. 612, l. 12; p. 613, l. 22&mdash;p. 614, l. 3; p. 619, l. 40&ndash;620, l. 26: <EM>Hyman</EM>; AB p. 239&ndash;562: <EM>Prosecution Report</EM></P1></P>
<P>8. As agent prosecutor, Mr. Jones was expected to liaise with the CRA, to review the documents and evidence, and to consult with the supervising PPSC counsel within the Economic Crimes Group. Ms. Hyman and Mr. Jones discussed the evidence and consulted on the form of specific charges and initial sentencing position. Ms. Hyman instructed Mr. Jones on how to proceed based on the facts discussed. As agent prosecutor, Mr. Jones was bound by the decisions of Ms. Hyman with respect to whom to charge, with what, sentencing position and whether a prosecution should continue. He was responsible for drafting the specific charges in consultation with the PPSC. Mr. Jones could not decide to charge or not charge other than as Ms. Hyman directed.
<P1>Ts. V. 1, p. 142, l. 14&mdash;p. 144, l. 34: <EM>McLean</EM>; Ts. V. 2, p. 571, l. 12 to p. 572, l. 10; p. 580, l. 42&mdash;p. 582, l. 10: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 629, l. 43&mdash;p. 630, l. 32; p. 613, l. 22&mdash;p. 614, l. 3: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 629, l. 38&mdash;p. 630, l.32: <EM>Jones</EM></P1></P>
<P>9. Mr. Jones consulted with the CRA for the figures to include in the charges to ensure he had the right quantum.
<P1>Ts. V. 3, p. 630, l. 33&ndash;42: <EM>Jones</EM></P1></P>
<P>10. The evidence available to the CRA and prosecutors before the charges were sworn included the following from the Prosecution Report:
<P1>a. the Respondents were joint shareholders and principals of their three businesses, MGM, Samaroo Holdings Ltd. (&ldquo;SHL&rdquo;) and Samaroo Motel Ltd . Their personal incomes were derived from the revenues of those businesses;</P1>
<P1>b. the MGM restaurant was open 24 hours per day and had one cash register. There were three shifts per day, each rung off with a separate till tape. There had been three shifts a day, rung off at the end of each shift, for the years 2003 to 2007 and earlier: AB p. 247; 252; 280;</P1>
<P1>c. the Respondents were both active in the businesses. They managed the MGM restaurant together. Mr. Samaroo's involvement included working in the kitchen, paying staff and suppliers, and preparing and providing the business' paperwork to the bookkeeper. Ms. Samaroo's role included working as a shift supervisor, managing the till during her shifts, training staff, paying suppliers and preparing end of shift paperwork. Ms. Samaroo also managed the nightclub, operated by SHL. She worked there three to four days per week: AB p. 247; 334; 360;</P1>
<P1>d. All paperwork and cash from the businesses were brought into an office space controlled by the Respondents within the MGM. Cash from the various businesses was commingled. Deposits were made to various joint personal and corporate bank accounts on an almost daily basis without connection to the underlying cash component of sales for that period: AB p. 247; 265;</P1>
<P1>e. Mr. Samaroo provided daily sales summary sheets with till tapes and other documentation for all the businesses to the bookkeeper, Deborah Ferens. Ms. Ferens posted the daily totals from the sales summary sheets to a monthly worksheet, which was the basis for the income tax and GST filings for the Respondents and their businesses: AB p. 260-261; 335; 360;</P1>
<P1>f. Ms. Ferens did not use the supporting till tapes themselves to prepare the monthly worksheet. She only posted sales data from the daily sales summary sheets provided to her by Mr. Samaroo. She would not be able to state which till tape or shift information she received: AB p. 251 at 6<SUP>th</SUP> bullet; 335;</P1>
<P1>g. Cash totaling $1,754,740 was deposited into the Respondents' accounts or used to pay suppliers in the relevant years without any known source, including:
<P2>i. Cash totaling $661,164 was deposited into the personal bank accounts but there were no recorded cash payments by the corporations to the Respondents: AB p. 264&ndash;266;</P2>
<P2>ii. Cash totaling $498,788 in excess of recorded sales receipts was deposited into the corporate bank accounts and cash payments of $594,788 were made for liquor, wages and suppliers for MGM. These amounts were credited to the shareholder loan account, reflecting an obligation owing by the corporation to the shareholder for these transactions. However, there were no cash withdrawals from the Respondents' personal bank accounts which could explain the origin of these cash amounts: AB p. 268&ndash;272;</P2>
<P2>iii. The corporations paid the Respondents for rental or management fees through journal entries crediting those amounts to the shareholder loan account. The corporations reduced this debt by paying amounts on behalf of the Respondents. There were no payments by cheque or transfers from the corporate bank accounts to the personal bank accounts of the Respondents. The expenditures made on behalf of the Respondents exceeded the amounts owing to them by the corporations for rent and GST: AB p. 266-267;</P2></P1>
<P1>h. A comparison of the periods before and after March 2006, when the audit by the CRA began, revealed the following:
<P2>i. The daily summary sheet for MGM received by Ms. Ferens prior to the audit had three columns marked &ldquo;Day&rdquo; and &ldquo;Night&rdquo; and &ldquo;Days Total&rdquo;. After the audit began, the sheet began to show four columns of data including a totals column: AB p. 251, last bullet; 253, last bullet; 360, entry for March 21, 2006, 2<SUP>nd</SUP> paragraph; 372: <EM>Daily Cash Report;</EM></P2>
<P2>ii. The daily sales amounts for MGM provided to the bookkeeper by Mr. Samaroo increased by about $50,000 per month, or an average of approximately $1,500 per day after the audit began. However, food costs, menu items and prices, and the makeup and volume of customers remained about the same: AB p. 253&ndash;260;</P2>
<P2>iii. The amounts deposited to the business accounts from merchant cards (Visa, Mastercard, etc.) remained constant. However, the ratio of cash sales to merchant card sales for MGM increased from between 24% and 35% of sales being paid by cash in the three years prior to the audit to 51% of sales being paid by cash after the audit commenced: AB 259;</P2>
<P2>iv. The reported gross revenue on the tax return of MGM for the taxation year ending February 28, 2007, the year after the audit, was approximately $500,000 higher than each of the previous two years. However, the reported cost of sales was approximately the same as in each of the previous two years: AB 284;</P2>
<P2>v. Monthly reported sales receipts for SHL, which ran the nightclub, increased by 33% over the previous years' average after the audit began. The reported revenue on the tax return for SHL for the taxation year ending February 28, 2007, was approximately $85,000 higher than the previous year with slightly lower operating expenses: AB 275-276; 284-285;</P2></P1>
<P1>i. During the audit, Mr. Samaroo responded to the auditor's questions about increased sales and the source of the cash used for deposits and payments by providing the following information:
<P2>i. they only recently began doing three ring-offs of the MGM till: AB 360-361;</P2>
<P2>ii. the cash was from savings over many years held in safety deposit boxes and deposited due to fear that the banks would not accept old bills. He did not know how much cash was in the safety deposit boxes or how much he took out each time to make a deposit: AB 361&ndash;363;</P2>
<P2>iii. the increase in monthly revenue was due to increased sales from a better economy, a competitor closing down and price increases. However, he had no explanation as to how revenue from food sales could increase when the cost of supplies for those food sales had not also increased: AB p. 362; 364;</P2>
<P2>iv. he did not know what percentage of his customers paid in cash versus merchant cards: AB 362; 364;</P2></P1>
<P1>j. Mr. Kendal reviewed historical reported family income and debt obligations for the Respondents. In his opinion it was not possible for the cash to have come from savings prior to the 2004, nor was it logical that the Respondents would have held it rather than apply it to debt. Neither Respondent had any taxable income until 1986. From 1990 to 1997 the reported family income averaged $64,000. From 1988 to the date of the audit the Respondents had multiple mortgages and loans, some with high rates of interest. As of January 2003 the Respondents had over $1,000,000 in commercial mortgages outstanding: AB p. 280&ndash;282;</P1></P>
<P>11. A 21-count Information charging the Respondents, MGM and SHL was prepared in Mr. Jones' office and sworn by Keith Kendal on June 12, 2008.
<P1>Ts. V.3, p. 635, l.41&mdash;p. 636, l. 16: <EM>Jones</EM>; AB p. 126&ndash;131: <EM>Information</EM></P1></P>
<P>12. Ms. Hyman and Mr. Jones continued to consult from the time charges were sworn throughout the criminal trial. Ms. Hyman decided what the initial sentencing position would be and communicated that to Mr. Jones.
<P1>Ts. V. 2, p. 586, l. 25&mdash;V. 3, p. 589, l. 34: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 590, l. 45&mdash;p. 593, l. 20: <EM>Hyman</EM> Ts. V.3, p. 630, l. 21-27-29; p. 645, l. 3&ndash;38: <EM>Jones</EM></P1></P>
<P>13. Mr. Jones and Ms. Hyman each reviewed the case and believed it met the charge approval standard of a reasonable prospect of conviction and in the public interest.
<P1>Ts. V. 2, p. 596, l. 29&ndash;32: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 600, l. 11&ndash;16; p. 621, l. 32&ndash;46: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 641, l. 9&ndash;18: <EM>Jones</EM>.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>The Criminal Trial</TI>
<P>14. The criminal trial took 19 days over a period of five months. In her Reasons for Judgment (April 6, 2011, Nanaimo Registry File No. 65681), Saunders P.C.J. noted that the Crown called 24 witnesses and filed 51 exhibits; the defence called Mr. Samaroo as the only witness: AB p. 135-136, paras. 4-5. The trial judge found Mr. Samaroo to be credible and accepted his explanation, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that he chose not to use the cash he had saved in safety deposit boxes and obtained mortgages instead because he wanted to build up a good credit rating in Nanaimo and he did not trust banks; AB p. 150-151, para. 66. The trial judge found that there were discrepancies in the evidence of the auditor, Glen Foster and the investigator, Keith Kendal and flaws in the analysis of net worth. The trial judge held that even if she had not found Mr. Samaroo to be credible, she could not rely on Mr. Kendal's calculations of the amount of tax evaded: AB p. 155&ndash;157, paras. 82&ndash;88.</P>
<P>15. Accordingly, the trial judge found that the Crown's case was weak and the amount of tax evaded &ldquo;highly uncertain&rdquo;: AB p. 155, para. 83. The Respondents were acquitted of all charges.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>The Civil Trial</TI>
<P>16. The Respondents filed a Notice of Civil Claim against the CRA, Brian Jones and Brian Jones' law corporation on March 29, 2012. The civil trial proceeded before Mr. Justice Punnett against the CRA for malicious prosecution and <EM>Charter</EM> breach and against Brian Jones and his law corporation for malicious prosecution.</P>
<P>17. The Respondents alleged that the Crown could prove neither the <EM>actus reus</EM> nor the quantum for the offence of tax evasion as it could not prove which till tape or shift was not given to Ms. Ferens. The Respondents claimed that Mr. Kendal interfered with the prosecution decision by suppressing the information that Ms. Ferens did not look at the till tapes. The Respondents further alleged that Mr. Kendal falsified evidence of Ms. Ferens by amending her will-say to state that she only received one daily sales summary sheet for each day without confirming the amendment with her. The Respondents claimed Mr. Kendal did this because he knew that the case could not succeed without evidence of which till tape or shift had been reported and he did not want the prosecutors to realize there was no case.</P>
<P>18. Punnett J. accepted that the investigator had suppressed information that the bookkeeper could not identify which till tape or shift was unreported and that this information was crucial in proving the offence of tax evasion. He concluded that as the offence could not be proven, there was no reasonable and probable cause for the prosecution. He further held that the CRA initiated the prosecution. He found the CRA was motivated by an improper purpose as it pursued a prosecution knowing it lacked the required evidence and without regard for the presumption of innocence. <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER> (&ldquo;<EM>Reasons</EM>&rdquo;), paras. 196&ndash;198.</P>
<P>19. The CRA was found liable for malicious prosecution and for a section 7 <EM>Charter</EM> breach. The case against Brian Jones and his law corporation was dismissed due to lack of proof of malice.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ERRORS IN JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>20. There are four issues on this appeal:
<P1>1. Whether the trial judge erred in law in holding that the manner of fraud and the quantum of unreported income were necessary elements of proof of the offence of tax evasion;</P1>
<P1>2. Whether the trial judge erred in law by requiring the Appellant to prove the <EM>actus reus</EM> of tax evasion in order to establish reasonable and probable cause;</P1>
<P1>3. Whether the trial judge erred in law in finding that the circumstances known to the Crown prosecutor at the relevant time could not establish reasonable and probable cause to commence a prosecution; and</P1>
<P1>4. Whether the trial judge erred in law and in fact in finding that the CRA investigator suppressed or withheld material evidence from the Crown and that he was therefore motivated by malice.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>I.</N><TI>STANDARD OF REVIEW</TI>
<P>21. The Court of Appeal may review an order of the B.C. Supreme Court where there are errors of law and fact. Questions of law are reviewed on a correctness standard while questions of fact are reviewable on the basis of palpable and overriding error. For questions of mixed fact and law, correctness is the standard if the error may be characterized as one of law, but otherwise the standard of palpable and overriding error applies.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>8, 10, 36</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>22. In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. J.M.H.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 45 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada recognized four situations where a trial judge's shortcomings in assessing the evidence constitute an error of law. Three such situations are: (1) making a finding of fact for which there is no evidence; (2) assessing the evidence based on a wrong legal principle; and failing to consider all the evidence in relation to the ultimate issue.
<P1><EM>J.M.H.</EM>, <UNDER>2011 SCC 45 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 24&ndash;27, 29&ndash;31</P1></P>
<P>23. On an appeal this Court may make or give any order that could have been given by the court below. This Court may also draw inferences of fact.
<P1><EM>Court of Appeal Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 77 as amended, s. 9</P1></P>
<P>24. In this case there are three errors of law which fundamentally undermine the trial judge's analysis. First, the trial judge misapprehended the legal test for tax evasion and what must be proved for the elements to be established in a criminal trial. This led him to err by misapplying the test for reasonable and probable cause in the tort of malicious prosecution. His error regarding the law of tax evasion tainted his analysis of the tort. Thirdly, the trial judge reversed the onus of proof by requiring the Appellant to prove that the criminal allegations were in fact true.</P>
<P>25. Finally, the trial judge erred in law and in fact in finding that the CRA investigator, Mr. Kendal, had suppressed or withheld material evidence from the Crown and that this was evidence of malice.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>II.</N><TI>THE OFFENCES ALLEGED</TI>
<P>26. In order to assess whether a plaintiff in a malicious prosecution claim has established that no reasonable and probable cause existed, the court must consider the elements of the offence and whether those elements could be satisfied on the circumstances known to the prosecutor at the time the charges were laid. The trial judge erroneously found that proof of the <EM>actus reus</EM> required proof of the &ldquo;actual mechanics of the alleged evasion&rdquo;, which in turn depended on the Crown proving which till tapes were missing from the information given to the bookkeeper by Mr. Samaroo. Because the Crown could not prove the &ldquo;missing till-tape theory&rdquo;, the trial judge reasoned that this was a case which the CRA investigator knew from the start could never succeed and hence the investigator could never have held a reasonable belief in probable guilt: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 208.</P>
<P>27. The Respondents were charged under sections 239(1)(a) and (d) of the <EM>ITA</EM> and sections 327(1)(a) and (c) of the <EM>Excise Tax Act</EM> (<EM>ETA</EM>) for the personal and corporate taxation years of 2004, 2005 and 2006 both as individuals and as parties to the offences of their companies. The <EM>ETA</EM> and party offences are not discussed in this factum, as proof of their elements overlaps with those of the <EM>ITA</EM> offences.</P>
<P>28. Section 239(1) of the <EM>ITA</EM> states in relevant part:
<QUOTE><P>Every person who has</P>
<P>(a) made, or participated in, assented to or acquiesced in the making of, false or deceptive statements in a return, certificate, statement or answer filed or made as required by or under this Act of a regulation,</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>(d) willfully, in any manner, evaded or attempted to evade compliance with this Act or payment of taxes imposed by this Act...</P></QUOTE>
is guilty of an offence ...</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Filing a False Return: 239(1)(a)</TI>
<P>29. The <EM>ITA</EM> imposes a legal duty on all tax payers to report their income. The elements of this offence will be proven when the Crown demonstrates beyond a reasonable doubt that the accused:
<P1>a. made a false or deceptive statement in an income tax return in one or more of the years specified in the charge;</P1>
<P1>b. knew that the statement was false or deceptive; and</P1>
<P1>c. knew that the income tax return was filed with the taxing authority.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Millar</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 2039 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF></P2></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Tax Evasion: Section 239(1)(d)</TI>
<P>30. Subsection 239(1)(d) is not limited to specific conduct, but speaks in broad terms. The crime of evading tax contrary to s. 239(1)(d) is made out if the Crown proves that:
<P1>a. the accused had taxable income in one or more of the years in question;</P1>
<P1>b. the accused knew that there was tax payable on the income;</P1>
<P1>c. the accused voluntarily performed an act or engaged in a course of conduct that avoided or attempted to avoid the payment of tax owing under the ITA;</P1>
<P1>d. the accused engaged in the conduct for the purpose of avoiding or attempting to avoid payment of tax imposed by the Act or knowing that avoiding the payment of tax imposed by the Act was a virtually certain consequence of his actions.
<P2><EM>Millar</EM>, <UNDER>2016 BCSC 2039 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 41; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Klundert</SOC><CITE>2004 CanLII 21268</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[2004] 23 C.R. (6th) 274</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, paras. 40, 47</P2></P1></P>
<P>31. The Crown must lead evidence that the <EM>actus reus</EM> and the <EM>mens rea</EM> coexisted during the offence period: <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Balla</SOC><CITE>2009 BCPC 136 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>139</PARANUM></CASEREF>, upheld on appeal on a different point: <UNDER>2010 BCSC 486 (CanLII)</UNDER>. The Crown does not need to prove the precise amount of tax payable but it must prove that there was at least some tax payable in the relevant year: <EM>Millar</EM>, <UNDER>2016 BCSC 2039 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 42.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>1.</N><TI><EM>The Actus Reus of Tax Evasion</EM></TI>
<P>32. The Crown is not required to prove a particular &ldquo;scheme&rdquo; or &ldquo;artifice&rdquo; to satisfy the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offence. Where the necessary intent to evade taxes is present, then the specific manner in which the intent is carried out is not important. The plain words of the subsection specify it may be done &ldquo;in any manner&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Paveley</SOC><CITE>1976 CanLII 969</CITE><COURTJUR>SK CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, paras. 40&ndash;48.</P1></P>
<P>33. Filing false tax returns is a voluntary act which is virtually certain to result in avoiding the payment of tax owing. This satisfies the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offence of tax evasion.
<P1><EM>Millar</EM>, <UNDER>2016 BCSC 2039 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 51&ndash;53; <EM>Klundert</EM>, <UNDER>2004 CanLII 21268 (ON CA)</UNDER>, para. 42.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2.</N><TI><EM>The Mens Rea of Tax Evasion</EM></TI>
<P>34. The <EM>mens rea</EM> of tax evasion was described by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Klundert</EM>, <UNDER>2004 CanLII 21268 (ON CA)</UNDER>, at paragraph 46:
<QUOTE><P>...I think the fault component in s. 239(1)(d) is twofold. First, the accused must know that tax is owing under the Act and second, the accused must intend to avoid or intend to attempt to avoid payment of that tax. An accused intends to avoid, or intends to attempt to avoid, payment of taxes owing under the Act where that is his purpose, or where he knows that his course of conduct is virtually certain to result in the avoiding of tax owing under the Act ...</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>35. There is no requirement for a finding that the &ldquo;evasion&rdquo; be deceitful or underhanded.
<P1><EM>Klundert</EM>, <UNDER>2004 CanLII 21268 (ON CA)</UNDER>, paras. 40-41.</P1></P>
<P>36. Willful blindness or recklessness will satisfy the knowledge component for the <EM>mens rea</EM> of tax evasion.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Kennedy</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 638 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>SCC leave ref'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[2006] S.C.C.A. No. 15</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Breakell</SOC><CITE>2009 ABCA 173 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>3</EM>.</N><TI><EM>The Amount of Tax Evaded is Not an Element of the Offence</EM></TI>
<P>37. Proof of the amount of tax evaded is not an essential element of the offence. The amount is relevant only at sentencing where the degree or extent of the offence becomes an issue. It is sufficient to show that there is an obvious unreported amount of taxable income
<P1><EM>ITA</EM> s. 239(1)(f) and (g); <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Cormier</SOC><CITE>1986 CanLII 1178</CITE><COURTJUR>BC CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, paras. 16&ndash;18, which notes leave to SCC refused Nov. 24, 1986; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Rosie</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 1885 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Balla</EM>, <UNDER>2009 BCPC 136 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 104.; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Kelly</SOC><CITE>2004 ONCJ 320 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>124</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>38. If the Crown cannot prove the entire amount of alleged tax evaded, the judge can amend the information to the amount proven and convict on that basis.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Century 21 Ramos Realty Inc.</SOC><CITE>[1987] O.J. No. 178</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, para. 45.</P1></P>
<P>39. In summary, the law is clear that where the Crown can establish beyond a reasonable doubt that the accused voluntarily did not report amounts that are taxable as income, with the intent of paying less tax, the accused can be found guilty of tax evasion under section 239(1)(d). Voluntarily making or assenting to or acquiescing in the making of a false statement in a tax return will itself satisfy the elements of 239(1)(a).</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>III.</N><TI>THE TORT OF MALICIOUS PROSECUTION</TI>
<P>40. A plaintiff must prove four elements on a balance of probabilities to succeed in an action for malicious prosecution:
<P1>i. the defendant initiated or continued the prosecution against the plaintiff;</P1>
<P1>ii. the prosecution terminated in the plaintiff's favour;</P1>
<P1>iii. the prosecution was undertaken without reasonable and probable cause; and</P1>
<P1>iv. the prosecution was motivated by malice or a primary purpose other than that of carrying the law into effect.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Miazga v. Kvello Estate</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>3</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>It is the third element of the test that is primarily at issue in this case, though the trial judge also erred in considering the fourth element.</P>
<P>41. At trial, Punnett. J. accepted the Respondents' submission that the <EM>actus reus</EM> of tax evasion could not be proven because the Appellant could not show which till tape was missing from the information given to the bookkeeper by Mr. Samaroo. However, the evidence was clear that the bookkeeper worked from the daily sales summary sheets given to her by Mr. Samaroo; she never worked from the till tapes. The number of till tapes given to the bookkeeper and whether any of them were missing was entirely immaterial to proving the <EM>actus reus</EM> in this case. This fundamental error in law&mdash;that is, that the actual mechanics of the fraudulent scheme had to be proved&mdash;led to erroneous findings that there was no reasonable and probable cause, that the CRA investigator suppressed or withheld material information from the Crown and that he did so maliciously.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Errors Regarding the Test for Tax Evasion</TI>
<P>42. The trial judge erred in law by failing to properly identify the legal elements of tax evasion. He applied the wrong legal principles to the facts when he concluded that the <EM>actus reus</EM> of tax evasion could not be proved at the time the charges were laid.</P>
<P>43. The cornerstone of the Respondents' case was that neither the CRA investigator nor Mr. Jones could prove at the criminal trial which till tape or shift was not reported to the bookkeeper, Ms. Ferens, nor could they prove the quantum of unreported tax. The Respondents argued that therefore neither the investigator nor the Crown could have objectively believed that proof beyond a reasonable doubt <EM>could</EM> be proved. In acceding to this argument, the trial judge failed to properly apply the law regarding the elements of tax evasion. He correctly states the Appellant's position that the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offence is the Respondents' intentional false report of income to the accountant knowing the result will be false reporting of their taxable income: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 202. However, at paragraph 208 Punnett J. finds this is flawed as it does not show the &ldquo;actual mechanics&rdquo; of the alleged evasion. He states &ldquo;To say that the plaintiffs did not report income cannot be the <EM>actus reus</EM>&rdquo;. He came to this conclusion without applying the law regarding tax evasion though it is set out previously in his decision at paragraphs 98 to 105.</P>
<P>44. In particular, the case of <EM>Klundert</EM>, <UNDER>2004 CanLII 21268 (ON CA)</UNDER>, referred to at paragraph 99 of the trial judge's Reasons, defines the task of the prosecutor as proving that the accused voluntarily performed an act or engaged in a course of conduct that avoided or attempted to avoid payment of tax owing under the <EM>ITA</EM>. The <EM>actus reus</EM> will be satisfied where the accused is found to have unreported taxable income.
<P1><EM>Klundert</EM>, <UNDER>2004 CanLII 21268 (ON CA)</UNDER>, paras. 40&ndash;42.</P1></P>
<P>45. The trial judge's error regarding the legal test for tax evasion had cascading consequences for his analysis of the case as a whole. It affected his view of the significance of the evidence regarding the statements of Ms. Ferens's evidence. When the correct legal test is applied it is clear that any discrepancies in whether Ms. Ferens could or could not identify which shift or till tape was not recorded on the daily summary sheet were immaterial. The key facts from her testimony were that the daily sales information was provided by Mr. Samaroo and that those amounts were used to prepare the tax returns.</P>
<P>46. The only significance as to which till tape or shift was unreported is the impact on quantum. However, quantum is not an element of the offence of tax evasion. It is only relevant at sentencing: <EM>Cormier</EM>, <UNDER>1986 CanLII 1178 (BC CA)</UNDER>, paras. 13&ndash;19.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Reasonable and Probable Cause</TI>
<P>47. The onus is on the plaintiff to prove that the elements of the offence charged could not, from an objective standpoint, have been proven based on the information known to the prosecutor at the time the criminal proceedings were initiated: <EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 58, 63, 74&ndash;76. The requirement that the plaintiff prove a lack of reasonable and probable cause reflects a presumption that a public prosecution is properly brought and immune from judicial review absent a demonstrated abuse of the criminal process.</P>
<P>48. The existence of reasonable and probable cause is a question of law. A prosecution is properly brought if the evidence available when the decision to initiate or continue the prosecution was made <EM>could</EM> objectively result in a conviction. This standard for civil liability is lower than the standard for charge approval set out in federal Crown policy manuals of a reasonable prospect of conviction. Hence, the result at the criminal trial does not answer whether reasonable and probable cause existed at the relevant time.
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, 55, 63-64, 73&ndash;76; V. 2, p. 558 L. 15&ndash;21: <EM>Hyman</EM></P1></P>
<P>49. Investigators are not required to evaluate evidence as would a prosecutor. The Supreme Court of Canada confirmed this with respect to police investigators in <CASEREF><SOC>Hill v. Hamilton-Wentworth Regional Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2007 SCC 41 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>50</PARANUM></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>... Police are required to weigh evidence to some extent in the course of an investigation: (cite omitted). But they are not required to evaluate the evidence according to legal standards or to make legal judgments. That is the task of prosecutors, defence attorneys and judges ...</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>50. Investigators are therefore not required to assess whether the evidence establishes reasonable and probable cause before referring a case to a prosecutor, who will make the decision whether to proceed with charges.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Franklin v. Toronto Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>[2008] O.J. No. 5237</CITE><COURTJUR>ONSC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>2008 CanLII 67896</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, para. 39.</P1></P>
<P>51. Where a Crown prosecutor determines that there is a reasonable prospect of conviction, it is implicit that those who commenced an investigation had grounds to do so. This is because at law, the standard of a reasonable prospect of conviction in Crown policy manuals is a higher threshold than the tort standard of reasonable and probable cause. As a result, where an investigator recommends charges and the prosecutor approves them, the investigator is considered to have had evidence sufficient to found a conviction on the tort standard: <CASEREF><SOC>Pitney v. Toronto (City) Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 1013 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Franklin</EM>, <UNDER>2008 CanLII 67896 (ON SC)</UNDER>, paras. 39-40, 60, 65. This presumption is based on both the prosecutor and investigator having the same information regarding the grounds for the charges.</P>
<P>52. In any event, in this case the CRA investigator did have reasonable and probable cause on an objective standard and did subjectively hold a belief in the Respondents' guilt when he referred the case to the Crown for charge approval.</P>
<P>53. Reasonable and probable cause will not be negated by showing that a defendant had both exculpatory and inculpatory information. Discrepancies in the evidence as to what occurred are for the trier of fact. They do not undermine a finding of reasonable and probable grounds to lay charges.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Chmielewski v. Niagara (Regional Municipality) Police Services Board</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 51 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>54. If the court concludes, on the basis of what was known at the time the proceedings were initiated, that reasonable and probable cause objectively existed, the prosecution is properly brought and the claim for malicious prosecution will fail.
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 75.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Application to this Case: Errors in Assessing Reasonable and Probable Cause</TI>
<P>55. The onus is on the Respondents to show that reasonable and probable cause did not exist when charges were sworn. The only ground on which they alleged it did not exist was that the prosecution could not prove which till tape or shift was not being reported to the bookkeeper. The Respondents did not contest any of the evidence in the Statement of Facts above from which a trier of fact <EM>could</EM> infer that the cash was unreported business income. Since a trier of fact could draw such an inference, the Respondents failed to meet their onus.</P>
<P>56. The appropriate method of analysis is to determine the elements of the offence of tax evasion and whether they objectively were met on the evidence available to the prosecution at the time the charges were sworn. This is the process required by <EM>Miazga</EM> to properly apply the test for reasonable and probable cause. Any assessment of the evidence by other persons is irrelevant to this objective review by the trial judge.</P>
<P>57. The trial judge failed to apply the test for reasonable and probable cause as established in <EM>Miazga</EM>. In his analysis the trial judge makes a number of distinct legal errors:
<P1>a. While he sets out the elements of tax evasion at paragraphs 98 to 100 of his decision, he does not assess the available evidence on an objective basis to see if those elements are met. He failed to ask himself if the Respondents consciously did something that avoided tax, knowing tax was owing, and did that thing for the purpose of avoiding tax or knowing that it was virtually certain that avoidance of tax would result. Instead he frames the analysis around an incorrect understanding of the <EM>actus reus</EM>;</P1>
<P1>b. The trial judge relied on the decision of the criminal trial judge in rejecting the evidence put forward by the Appellants to demonstrate that reasonable and probable cause existed when the charges were sworn: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 206. This is directly contrary to the Supreme Court of Canada's warnings that care must be taken to review the facts based on what was known to the prosecutor when the charges were initiated, not what resulted at trial: <EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 55, 76;</P1>
<P1>c. The trial judge reversed the onus of proof. Rather than requiring the Respondents to prove a lack of reasonable and probable cause, he held that the material facts demonstrating the existence of reasonable and probable cause which were put forward by the Appellants &ldquo;have not been proven at this trial&rdquo;. <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 206. This is contrary to the law as set out in <EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER> at paras. 55 and 58;</P1>
<P1>d. The trial judge stated that &ldquo;there was never an explanation given as to how Ms. Helen Samaroo may have been involved in this alleged scheme of evasion&rdquo;. In doing so, he ignored the evidence of Ms. Hyman and contained in the Prosecution Report as to why the decision was also made to charge Ms. Samaroo: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 243. Finding that there was no evidence on this point when clearly there was some, is an error of law: <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. J.M.H.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 45 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>58. When the evidence set out in the Statement of Facts above is assessed against the legal test for tax evasion set out in <EM>Millar</EM> and <EM>Klundert</EM>, it is clear that reasonable and probable cause did exist. The evidence available to the prosecution showed that the business income reported to the bookkeeper, which was used to prepare the Respondents' income tax returns, did not reflect all the funds flowing into the hands of the Respondents. This conclusion is further strengthened by the evidence that once the audit commenced, the reporting of income changed: the costs of food remained the same, but the money taken in suddenly increased. Given the chance to explain this inconsistency, Mr. Samaroo could provide none. On the whole of the evidence a reasonable inference could be drawn by a trier of fact that the cash amounts put into the accounts and used to pay suppliers were unreported income from the businesses during the years in question and that the underreporting was deliberate.</P>
<P>59. By failing to properly analyse the elements of tax evasion, the trial judge erred in law in finding that the elements of the offence could not be met on the available evidence. A proper analysis of the available evidence demonstrates that the elements of tax evasion could be met by the prosecution at the time the charges were sworn. There is no evidence that any information was received after charges were laid which would have affected that assessment.</P>
<P>60. In summary, there was reasonable and probable cause to commence and continue the prosecution on an objective standard. Thus the order of the trial judge should be set aside. However, in the event this Court finds on an objective basis that reasonable and probable cause did not exist, the Appellant submits that the element of malice was not met on the evidence at trial.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>Malice or Improper Purpose</TI>
<P>61. Malicious prosecution is an intentional tort. Initiation of a prosecution without reasonable and probable cause is not sufficient to prove malicious prosecution; the plaintiff must also prove that the defendant set the criminal process in motion for an improper purpose, namely a purpose other than carrying the law into effect.
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 56; <CASEREF><SOC>Nelles v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 S.C.R. 170</CITE><PARANUM>51</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>62. The core meaning of malice in the tort of malicious prosecution is the use of the criminal justice system for a purpose other than to bring an offender to justice and thereby aid in the enforcement of the law.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Oniel v. Toronto (Metropolitan) Police Force</SOC><CITE>2001 CanLII 24091</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[2001] O.J. No. 90</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, paras. 42&ndash;44.</P1></P>
<P>63. Whether a defendant acted with malice or improper purpose is a question of fact. The plaintiff must adduce evidence as to the defendant's state of mind. Acting on an honest yet mistaken belief that reasonable and probable cause did exist is not inconsistent with carrying the law into effect. As a result, if a defendant had a <EM>bona fide</EM> belief that proof beyond a reasonable doubt could be made out, he or she will have acted for the proper purpose of giving effect to the law and the claim of malicious prosecution must fail.
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 78-79, 85.</P1></P>
<P>64. Actions taken in furtherance of a prosecution cannot be the basis of a malicious prosecution claim, as those actions are not for a collateral or improper purpose. Mishandling a prosecution does not amount to malice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McCreight v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 483 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>65. A plaintiff must prove that the defendant <EM>willfully</EM> perverted the criminal justice process. It is only where there is a fraud on the criminal justice process that malice can be said to exist. Malice does not include incompetence, inexperience, recklessness, gross negligence or poor judgment.
<P1><EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 78&ndash;80; <EM>Nelles</EM>, para. 55; <CASEREF><SOC>Proulx v. Quebec (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2001 SCC 66 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>35, 44-45</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>66. The trial judge held that &ldquo;proof of malice requires proof on a balance of probabilities that in the role of an investigator, Mr. Kendal acted deliberately to subvert and abuse his office&rdquo;: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 257. The trial judge held that this had been established, based on the following findings regarding Mr. Kendal:
<P1>a. he suppressed evidence and attributed evidence to witnesses that was not accurate;</P1>
<P1>b. he decided the Samaroos were guilty and set out to prove it even if to do so &ldquo;required a breach of his proper role and responsibilities&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>c. he knowingly misstated evidence essential to proof of the <EM>actus reus</EM>; and</P1>
<P1>d. he filed a misleading report knowing it would be relied upon to authorize the prosecution.</P1></P>
<P>67. The trial judge also relied on what he held to be indicators of &ldquo;an unfortunate culture&rdquo; within the CRA, including:
<P1>a. reference in the Primary Report to two factors supporting the case being referred to full investigation that: 1) restaurant and night club industries are those that have a high rate of non-compliance; and 2) that CRA had not prosecuted a business in the restaurant or nightclub industry in Nanaimo recently: AB 15: <EM>Primary Report</EM>;</P1>
<P1>b. the CRA publicizes convictions for tax evasion and &ldquo;boasts&rdquo; of an 89% conviction rate: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 259(d); and</P1>
<P1>c. the trial judge found that &ldquo;CRA was seeking substantial terms of imprisonment and significant penalties&rdquo; in imposing punitive damages: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 330.</P1></P>
<P>68. These conclusions regarding the CRA are errors in law and in fact. There was no evidence before the court to support these rulings.</P>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>1</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Errors in The Findings of Fact Against Mr. Kendal</EM></TI>
<P>69. The trial judge held that Mr. Kendal misled the prosecutors as he did not tell them that Ms. Ferens she could not identify which till tape or shift she did or did not receive. This information was contained in Ms. Ferens' interview by Terry Finlay. The trial judge held that this was material information that would have impacted the prosecution decision as the case could not be proven without this evidence. He found that Mr. Kendal knew the case could not be proven based on the Finlay interview, and suppressed the information about that interview in order to have the case continue to move forward. He held that this established that Mr. Kendal initiated the prosecution for an improper purpose.
<P1><EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 197, 231</P1></P>
<P>70. There is no evidence that Mr. Kendal suppressed key information and thereby misled the prosecutors. The fact that Ms. Ferens was working from the daily summary sheets and not from till tapes is specifically noted or can be inferred from the following statements in the final Prosecution Report:
<P1>a. &ldquo;Debbie Ferens will be able to explain that from each completed &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; summary sheets, she would post the sales data to her monthly spreadsheet...&rdquo;: AB p. 251, Element #3, bullet 2;</P1>
<P1>b. &ldquo;Debbie Ferens <UNDER>will not be able to state that she knew which till tape shifts she received during the periods leading up to February 2006</UNDER>: the morning, the evening or the graveyard shifts, as she only posted the data from the filled out daily sales sheet summary provided to her with the till tapes from Tony Samaroo.&rdquo; (emphasis added): AB p. 251, Element #4, bullet 2;</P1>
<P1>c. &ldquo;Debbie Ferens (Witness #4) will be able to attest to using the information provided by the Samaroos from the &ldquo;Daily Cash Reports&rdquo; and posting this to her monthly spreadsheet...&rdquo;: AB p. 260, Element #10, bullet 3;</P1>
<P1>d. &ldquo;Debbie Ferens will be able to explain that from each days completed &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; summary sheets, she would post the sales data to her monthly spreadsheet...&rdquo;: AB p. 274, first bullet;</P1>
<P1>e. &ldquo;Debbie Ferens will be able to attest to using the information provided by the Samaroos and posting this to her monthly spreadsheet...&rdquo;: AB p. 274, Element #4 bullet 3;</P1>
<P1>f. &ldquo;Ferens received from Tony Samaroo a filled out &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; sheet listing only two till tapes of data per day, with the till tapes attached. Ferens posted from these &lsquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; sheets the applicable daily sales data onto the monthly summary sales sheet...&rdquo;: AB p. 335, second and third bullets;</P1>
<P1>g. &ldquo;The daily summary sheet used to only show 2 ring offs a day. The bookkeeper stated that she only posted 2 ring offs a day for the period under audit (lump sum total put on the monthly summary sheet)...&rdquo;: AB p. 360, second paragraph in entry for March 21, 2006;</P1>
<P1>h. &ldquo;the bookkeeper prepares a monthly revenue spreadsheet, crediting the various sales accounts and GST &amp; PST payable accounts, based on the &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; as provided to her from Samaroo, and not from the supporting till tapes themselves...&rdquo;: AB p. 451, para. (3);</P1></P>
<P>71. It is clear from these excerpts that the prosecution, Mr. Kendal and thence the defence had the same information about Ms. Ferens' expected testimony, including that she did not work from till tapes.</P>
<P>72. The information in these excerpts from the Prosecution Report is also not materially different from the statement Ms. Ferens gave to investigator Terry Finlay during the search which took place in January of 2007. The notes report Ms. Ferens as saying &ldquo;I don't post from the tapes because the daily sales sheet is adequate.&rdquo;
<P1>AB p.20, question 7</P1></P>
<P>73. The witness statement of Ms. Ferens disclosed at trial dated February 9, 2010 is also consistent with the prior statements. That witness statement includes the following:
<P1>a. &ldquo;Upon receipt of the daily cash report sheet form (sic) the client she would complete the form, by summarizing the amount for the day in the 3<SUP>rd</SUP> column entitled &ldquo;Days Total&rdquo; for the days total of sales receipts.&rdquo;: AB p. 164, last paragraph;</P1>
<P1>b. &ldquo;She does not recall ever looking at the supporting till tape data that accompanies the &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; and the sales chits (for charge card sales) as there is no need to in order to do the bookkeeping from. (sic).&rdquo;: AB p. 165, first paragraph; and</P1>
<P1>c. &ldquo;She would then post from the &ldquo;Days Total&rdquo; sales receipts to a monthly spreadsheet...&rdquo;: AB p. 165, second to last paragraph.</P1></P>
<P>74. There is no evidence that at the time the charges were sworn the prosecutors expected that Ms. Ferens could identify which till tape or shift she did or did not receive. It is clear from the evidence that that the prosecution was fully aware that Ms. Ferens worked only from the daily summary sheets and could not identify which till tape or shifts were reflected in those summaries. There is no evidence to support a finding that this information was suppressed or withheld from the prosecutors. As a result there is no evidence that Mr. Kendal suppressed evidence in order to mislead the prosecutors into pursuing the prosecution.</P>
<P>75. Further, as noted in the analysis of reasonable and probable cause, the information about which till tape or shift was not reported to Ms. Ferens is immaterial. The <EM>actus reus</EM> is satisfied by the deliberate act of providing Ms. Ferens with inaccurate daily summary sheets which the Respondents knew would form the basis of their tax returns and therefore result in less tax owing. The inaccuracy of the daily summary sheets can be demonstrated by reference to the bank statements, business practices and available records. Which shift or till tape is only relevant to a determination of the amount of tax evaded, which is not an element of the offence.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>2</EM>.</N><TI><EM>The Evidence as to Who Made the Prosecution Decision</EM></TI>
<P>76. The judge misapprehended the evidence when he concluded that Mr. Kendal was in effect responsible for the prosecution of the Respondents and not the Crown. This was due to his erroneous conclusions on the <EM>actus reus</EM> and reasonable and probable cause.</P>
<P>77. The prosecution of the Respondents was a public prosecution. It was therefore presumptively brought by the Attorney General of Canada or her delegated agents, in this case Mr. Jones, Ms. McLean and Ms. Hyman. The evidence demonstrates that these individuals had particular roles and responsibilities at various stages of the prosecution continuum.</P>
<P>78. Ms. McLean, Mr. Jones and Ms. Hyman all testified as to the process of assessing the information from the CRA against the PPSC charge approval standard, the decision as to whether to proceed summarily or by way of indictment, formalizing the charges, the decision on the initial sentencing position, and the relationship between in-house PPSC counsel and the agent appointed. The evidence clearly shows that the underlying decisions were made by the PPSC, in particular Ms. Hyman.</P>
<P>79. There was nothing nefarious about Mr. Kendal being in contact with the prosecutors and discussing the proposed charges and the relevant evidence. This is a normal result of being the investigator on the case. A public prosecutor necessarily depend on investigators for the information on which the case proceeds. In any criminal case it is the investigator who, through his summary of available evidence, identifies who is accused, of what offences, and what evidence supports the charges. In the case of tax evasion, the amounts alleged to have been evaded are calculated by the investigator based on available information, therefore the investigator will be the witness to prove the amounts.</P>
<P>80. There is no evidence that the role of Mr. Kendal was in any way outside the normal one for an investigator on such a case. The evidence of Ms. Hyman is that discussions with the investigators regarding the charges was part of the process as the CRA investigator and prosecutor must be in agreement that reasonable grounds existed in order for the investigator to swear the information. The investigator was also expected to set out information about potential defences so that the prosecution could consider them. Ms. McLean testified that the prosecutor relied on the investigators for information used to determine if charges would go forward, and could request further investigation if information was lacking. This indicates an expectation of ongoing interaction.
<P1>Ts. V. 3, p. 589, l. 44&mdash;p. 590, l. 15: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 2, p. 578, l. 20&ndash;29: <EM>Hyman;</EM> Ts. V. 1, p. 126, l. 17-p. 127, l. 2: <EM>McLean</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>81. The Respondents point to an email attaching 88 charges as evidence that the CRA drafted and swore the charges against them without any independent assessment by the prosecutors. However, the Information sworn against the Respondents had 21 charges and was drafted by Marsha Down, a lawyer in Mr. Jones' law firm.
<P1>Ts. V.3, p. 635, l.41&mdash;p. 636, l. 16: <EM>Jones</EM>; AB p. 126&ndash;131: <EM>Information</EM></P1></P>
<P>82. The testimony of Mr. Kendal, Ms. McLean, Ms. Hyman and Mr. Jones was unanimous that the PPSC had the decision-making authority on whether a prosecution went ahead or not and on what basis.
<P1>Ts. V. 1, p. 125, l. 27&mdash;p. 126, l. 16: <EM>McLean</EM>; Ts. V. 2, p. 567, l. 33&mdash;p. 568, l. 10; p. 571, l. 16&mdash;p. 572, l. 10: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 630, l. 17&ndash;29: <EM>Jones</EM>; Ts. V. 2, p. 310, l. 12&ndash;28; p. 498, l. 3&mdash;p. 499, l. 26: <EM>Kendal</EM></P1></P>
<P>83. The evidence at trial is clear that the information relied on for assessing whether the prosecution standard had been met prior to charges being sworn came from the Prosecution Report. Both Janna Hyman and Brian Jones reviewed the Prosecution Report. Both held the view that prosecution was justified.
<P1>Ts. V. 2, p. 572, l. 44: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 596, l. 25&ndash;32; p. 600, l. 11&ndash;18;p. 620, l. 17&ndash;33: <EM>Hyman</EM>; Ts. V. 3, p. 641, l. 9&ndash;18: <EM>Jones</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>84. With respect to consideration of the <EM>actus reus</EM>, Brian Jones testified that he did not consider what in particular Ms. Ferens looked at to be the significant factor in the prosecution's case. Ms. Hyman testified that the evidence of Ms. Ferens went to how the evasion was being committed, namely to trace back from a filed tax return how the information got into the tax return, in this case by the bookkeeper inputting data received from Mr. Samaroo.
<P1>Ts. V. 3, p. 699, l.29&mdash;p. 700, l. 10: <EM>Jones;</EM> Ts. V. 2, p. 576, l. 33&ndash;577, l. 14<EM>: Hyman</EM></P1></P>
<P>85. In summary, the trial judge erred in law and in fact in finding Mr. Kendal suppressed information and misled the prosecutors with respect to the evidence Ms. Ferens could provide, thereby subverting the prosecution process. When the whole of the evidence available at the relevant time is considered, it is clear that the prosecutors knew at the time the charges were sworn that Ms. Ferens could not identify which till tapes or shifts were recorded on the daily sales summaries received from Mr. Samaroo. That information was taken into account by the prosecutors in assessing whether the standard of reasonable prospect of conviction was met. As a result, there is no basis for finding that Mr. Kendal initiated an unfounded prosecution.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>3</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Mr. Kendal's Subjective Belief in Guilt</EM></TI>
<P>86. The trial judge found that Mr. Kendal acted with an improper purpose as he hoped to convict the Respondents because he believed they were guilty: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 257. Thus, Punnett J. accepted that Mr. Kendal believed in the Respondents' guilt and that his purpose was to bring them before a criminal court for trial. <EM>Miazga</EM> confirms that such a subjective belief will insulate a person from a malicious prosecution finding even when there is a lack of reasonable and probable cause where the person has a mistaken but honest belief that cause exists. This is because where a person acts with the subjective belief that the accused is guilty, the person is acting for a purpose consistent with that of a prosecution, namely bringing an accused before a court for determination of guilt or innocence. However, if the objective grounds for reasonable and probable cause is &ldquo;woefully inadequate&rdquo;, an absence of subjective believe may be inferred: <EM>Miazga</EM>, <UNDER>2009 SCC 51 (CanLII)</UNDER>, paras. 79-80.</P>
<P>87. In this case, the prosecutors assessed the evidence Mr. Kendal provided and found that it met the reasonable prospect of conviction standard. It was therefore reasonable for Mr. Kendal to believe the available evidence could prove the case. As noted above, when the test for tax evasion is properly applied, the evidence did objectively support reasonable and probable cause.</P>
<P>88. Mr. Kendal's subjective belief was therefore reasonably based. There is no evidence that it was not honestly held. As a result, there is no evidence supporting the trial judge's finding that he was acting for an improper purpose.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>4</EM>.</N><TI><EM>The Findings of Fact Against the CRA</EM></TI>
<P>89. With respect to the references to the CRA as an organization, there was no evidence at trial that consideration by the CRA of the factors referenced in the Primary Report or publication of convictions for tax evasion were inappropriate. If the whole of the Primary Report is considered, there is a detailed description of the alleged tax evasion by the Respondents, following which is the reference to these two additional factors. The trial judge does not indicate on what basis he concludes that these two factors are inappropriate for consideration or how they relate to the &ldquo;improper purpose&rdquo; attributed to Keith Kendal.</P>
<P>90. There is also no evidence that the Appellant sought or had any input into the initial sentencing position. The undisputed evidence of Mr. Jones and Ms. Hyman is that Ms. Hyman determined what sentence should be sought.</P>
<P>91. The Appellant has a mandate to support the enforcement of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>: <EM>Canada Revenue Agency Act</EM>, S.C. 1999, c. 17, s. 2 (definition of &ldquo;program legislation&rdquo;) and s. 5(1)(a). Investigating those suspected of tax evasion and recommending prosecution based on the available evidence is consistent with that statutory mandate. Deterring others from breaching the <EM>ITA</EM> by publicizing that persons have been convicted by a court of law is also consistent with that statutory mandate. There is no evidence to the contrary.</P>
<P>92. Mr. Kendal testified that when he referred the case to the PPSC he believed there was a case and that the Respondents were guilty: Ts. V. 2, p. 401, l. 3&ndash;12; p. 419, l. 31&ndash;38; p. 548, l. 15, - 31; p. 552, l. 13&ndash;19: <EM>Kenda</EM>l. This evidence shows he believed there was reasonable and probable cause for the prosecution. There is no evidence that Mr. Kendal, in referring the case to the Crown for charge approval, had any purpose other than to have the Crown assess whether a criminal case should proceed to court. There are no grounds for a finding of improper purpose on the part of Mr. Kendal or, vicariously, on the part of the Appellant.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>Section 7 <EM>Charter</EM> Breach</TI>
<P>93. The trial judge held that the Appellant breached the Respondents' section 7 <EM>Charter</EM> rights by initiating the prosecution when it was wrongful to do so. He held that Mr. Kendal &ldquo;suppressed exculpatory evidence from the defence&rdquo; and &ldquo;created inculpatory evidence&rdquo; in order to obtain a conviction: <EM>Reasons</EM>, <UNDER>2018 BCSC 324 (CanLII)</UNDER>, para. 289. His judgment on section 7 reflects the same misunderstanding of the law and the evidence that led to his erroneous conclusions on the allegation of malicious prosecution.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>1.</N><TI><EM>No Exculpatory Evidence was Suppressed</EM></TI>
<P>94. The trial judge does not set out what &ldquo;exculpatory evidence&rdquo; was suppressed. The only evidence which Mr. Kendal allegedly suppressed related to what Ms. Ferens would say in testimony. That evidence related to whether the prosecutor could prove which till tape or shift was unreported, which was immaterial. It was not exculpatory evidence.</P>
<P>95. The explanations provided by the Respondents about where the cash came from was exculpatory evidence. It was included in the Prosecution Report along with the evidence as to why the investigator did not accept the explanations.
<P1>AB p. 277&ndash;282</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2.</N><TI><EM>No Inculpatory Evidence was Created</EM></TI>
<P>96. The trial judge does not set out what inculpatory evidence was created. This appears to refer to Mr. Kendal adding to Ms. Ferens' will-say statement that she was expected to testify to only receiving one daily summary sheet from Mr. Samaroo.</P>
<P>97. The alteration of the will-say to reflect expected testimony without confirmation from the witness that she did in fact only receive one summary sheet per day is not an advisable practice. However and in any event, this was not material to the Crown's case. Regardless of how many daily summary sheets she received, the inculpatory aspect of Ms. Ferens' evidence is that the income reported in the tax returns derives from information provided to her by Mr. Samaroo. The Respondents did not dispute that she could give this evidence. Accordingly, there is no basis for a finding that inculpatory evidence was created by Mr. Kendal.</P>
<P>98. In the result, the Respondents failed to prove an absence of reasonable and probable cause. Nor did the Respondents prove that the CRA investigator withheld material evidence or misled the Crown in any way whatsoever or that he was motivated by any improper purpose.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>99. The Appellant seeks an Order that:
<P1>a. the appeal be allowed and the trial judgment set aside; and</P1>
<P1>b. the Appellant receive the costs of the appeal and the trial below.</P1></P>
<P>100. The parties have agreed, in the event this Court dismisses the appeal, the legal costs of the defence at the criminal trial are reduced and settled at $287,221.77.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, this 29<SUP>th</SUP> day of June, 2018.</P>
