<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>This is a case in which the Crown failed to fulfill its prosecutorial responsibilities. Brian Jones too readily left control of the prosecution, disclosure, and decision making to Keith Kendal and the CRA, and Mr. Jones and PPSC failed to properly discharge their respective charge assessment and approval obligations. Mr. Jones relied on and deferred to Mr. Kendal and in doing so permitted the office of the Attorney General to become simply an extension of the CRA and Mr. Kendal. These failings permitted Keith Kendal to accomplish what he had set out from the inception of his investigation to achieve: to do everything within his power to ensure that the respondents were charged, prosecuted, convicted and imprisoned.</P>
<P>The presumption of innocence was meaningless to Mr. Kendal. He assumed that the respondents were guilty of tax evasion. Mr. Kendal started with the deposits, and then worked backwards to manufacture a case against the respondents based on a theory of evasion Mr. Kendal knew could not be proved. Mr. Kendal acted deliberately to subvert and abuse his office, by supressing evidence and attributing evidence to witnesses that he knew was not accurate. Mr. Kendal knowingly misstated evidence essential to the proof of the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the alleged offences, prepared a misleading Prosecution Report knowing it would be relied upon by the Crown to determine if charges should proceed, and misled Lisa McLean at the PPSC as to the evidence that could be mustered in support of his theory. His clear intent was to see that criminal charges were laid and the respondents prosecuted irrespective of the evidence.</P>
<P>The appellant fails to address any of the key findings of fact made by the trial judge. The errors alleged by the appellant are based on a selective and distorted reading of the trial judge's Reasons for Judgment. Overall, the appellant's submission amounts to an invitation to this Court to ignore the findings of fact of the trial court below.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. The appellant's statement of facts is incomplete. The appellant ignores critical findings of fact made by the trial judge and misstates findings in ways that are misleading. It is important to note that at trial, the appellant also failed to address any of the evidence in support of the respondents' claim nor did the appellant address the &lsquo;key issue&rsquo; of what evidence ever existed to prove the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the alleged offences. Most of the Respondent's arugment is being made for the first time before this Court. The trial judge found:
<QUOTE><P>[201] The defence provided a 40 page written submission that canvased the legal issues raised. Curiously in both their written and oral submissions the defence chose not to address any of the facts that support the plaintiffs' claim of malicious prosecution nor did they address the key issue of the mechanics of the <EM>actus reus</EM>. Instead in their written submission they simply stated:
<QUOTE><P>There is no evidence in this case that displaces the presumption that reasonable and probable cause existed. Nor is there any evidence that any defendant acted for a purpose other than placing the case before the court for adjudication.</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE>
<P1>Appeal Record (A.R.), p. 76, para. 201</P1></P>
<P>2. The respondents have set out below the key findings of fact as found by the trial judge.</P>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>A.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Civil Audit by the Canada Revenue and Referral for Criminal Investigation:</UNDER></TI>
<P>3. Beginning in March 2006, the appellant conducted a civil audit of the respondents. On March 21, 2006, Glen Foster, a civil auditor with the CRA, interviewed Deborah Ferens, the bookkeeper for the respondents. Ms. Ferens provided Mr. Foster with a copy of the daily sales summary sheet for the restaurant that showed three columns described as &ldquo;day&rdquo;, &ldquo;night&rdquo;, and &ldquo;days total&rdquo;. Mr. Foster recorded in his notes that Ms. Feren's told him as follows:
<QUOTE><P>the daily summary sheet used to only show 2 ring offs a day. The bookkeeper stated that she only posted 2 ring offs a day for the period under audit.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Appeal Record (A.R.) p. 24/25, para. 14</P1></P>
<P>4. The appellant makes reference at paragraph 2 of their statement of facts to the respondents' having &ldquo;destroyed&rdquo; their source documents, including till tapes. It must be emphasized that no adverse inference was drawn by the judge in the criminal trial from the fact that the daily sales summary sheet, till tapes, and other source documents were not retained by the respondents after the documents were returned to them by their bookkeeper. The judge in the criminal trial expressly declined to draw the adverse inference urged by the Crown in that trial, and apparently suggested by the appellant in this appeal&mdash;that the respondents deliberately destroyed their source documents. The criminal trial judge also noted that the allegation that the records may have been deliberately destroyed, together with other key allegations, were never put to Tony Samaroo by the Crown.
<P1>Appeal Book (&ldquo;A.B.&rdquo;), p. 152, para. 72. See also related para. 76.</P1></P>
<P>5. As found by the trial judge, Mr. Foster determined that during the audit period substantial cash deposits had been made to the respondents' business accounts. These deposits and their source precipitated, and were the foundation for, the criminal prosecution.
<P1>A.R. p. 25, para. 15</P1></P>
<P>6. Mr. Foster also interviewed Tony Samaroo and Mr. Ed Heese, the respondents' long standing accountant. Both Mr. Heese and Mr. Samaroo explained to Mr. Foster that the source of the deposits were cash savings that Mr. Samaroo had accumulated over many years. Mr. Heese and Mr. Samaroo explained that Mr. Samaroo, afraid that the banks would stop accepting old $100 bills, began depositing the bills into the business accounts. Mr. Heese confirmed that Mr. Samaroo told him in 2005 that he had started depositing his old $100 bills into his personal and corporate bank accounts, a year prior to the start of the civil audit.
<P1>A.R. p. 25, paras. 16 and 17</P1>
<P1>A.B. p. 147, para. 53</P1></P>
<P>7. Following the completion of the civil audit, on August 18, 2006, Glen Foster referred the case to the Enforcement Division of the CRA for a determination as to whether or not a criminal investigation would be undertaken. Alan Jones, team leader with the appellant, authored a &ldquo;Primary Report&rdquo; dated October 30, 2006, recommending that the case proceed to a full investigation, including that searches be conducted at the respondents' residence, three business locations, the accountant's office and the auditor's desk.
<P1>A.R. p. 25, para. 18</P1></P>
<P>8. Mr. Alan Jones wrote in his Primary Report that two other factors justified the case being selected for criminal investigation apart from the results of the civil audit:
<QUOTE><P>1. The restaurant and night club industries are those that have a high rate of non-compliance; and,</P>
<P>2. CRA has not prosecuted a business in the restaurant or nightclub industry in the Nanaimo area recently.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 25, para. 19</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>B.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>The Criminal Investigation and the Preparation of the Draft Prosecution Report:</UNDER></TI>
<P>9. On January 24, 2007, the search warrants in relation to the respondents' residence, businesses and the accountant's office were executed. Keith Kendal was assigned as the officer in charge regarding the search of the respondents' residence. Terry Finlay, another investigator with the CRA, was the officer in charge of the search of the accountant's office (Mr. Heese).
<P1>A.R. p. 26, para. 21</P1></P>
<P>10. During the course of the search of the accountant's office, Mr. Finlay interviewed Deborah Ferens, the respondents' bookkeeper. This was the second time she had been interviewed and the first time as part of the criminal investigation. Mr. Finlay recorded Ms. Ferens' answers on a sheet that had pre-prepared (typed) questions. He wrote that Ms. Ferens did not look at the till tapes provided to her (and thus did not know and could not say how many till tapes she was being provided with); she worked only from the daily sales summary sheet.
<P1>A.R. p. 26, para. 22</P1></P>
<P>11. Mr. Kendal was aware prior to the investigation being assigned to him that the CRA had no till tapes. He testified that following the search, the officers would have gathered for a scrum to discuss the searches and what evidence had been obtained. This would probably have included a review of the interview of Ms. Ferens.
<P1>A.R. p. 26/27, para. 23</P1></P>
<P>12. Mr. Kendal testified that he understood Ms. Ferens' explanation to Mr. Finlay to mean that she did not know how many till tapes were being provided to her by the respondents. She could not say whether she received two or three till tapes, nor what shifts they related to.
<P1>A.R. p. 27, para. 24</P1></P>
<P>13. As of January 27, 2007 the CRA knew that Ms. Ferens did not look at the till tapes and could not say whether the summary sheet included income from two or three shifts. At this point the CRA also knew that they did not have the till tapes or summary sheets for 2004 or 2005.
<P1>A.R. p. 82/83, para. 215</P1></P>
<P>14. In a working paper created approximately a month after the execution of the search warrants, Mr. Kendal wrote that he &ldquo;cannot show that only two ring ups (sic) were reported on 2004 &amp; 2005... Cannot prove 3<SUP>rd</SUP> shift wasn't reported so this would be meaningless&rdquo;. The appellant formally admitted that these statements accurately reflected Mr. Kendal's subjectively held view of the case at the time it was written.
<P1>A.R. p. 27, para. 25, 26</P1></P>
<P>15. Mr. Kendal did not prepare a will-say statement based on Ms. Ferens' interviews either by Mr. Foster or Mr. Finlay. He made no mention of her second interview, by Mr. Finlay, in either the draft Prosecution Report or the Final Prosecution Report nor did Mr. Kendal disclose the existence of Finlay's interview to Lisa McLean or Jana Hyman at PPSC. He testified that Mr. Brian Jones was &lsquo;presumably&rsquo; aware if its existence but denied telling Mr. Jones about it.
<P1>A.R., p. 64, para. 152</P1></P>
<P>16. Mr. Kendal was responsible for disclosure during the prosecution and he prepared and disclosed all 88 binders of disclosure. Mr. Kendal also chose not to disclose the notes of Mr. Finlay's interview of Ms. Ferens in the witness statement binder provided to the respondents. Instead, he placed it in a large binder of search materials referred to in the criminal trial as Binder &ldquo;D&rdquo;. There was no reference to the interview or the notes in the table of contents of Binder &ldquo;D&rdquo;. Unless there was an issue related to the searches, which there was not, there would be no reason to review Binder &ldquo;D&rdquo;.
<P1>A.R. p. 64, para. 153 and p. 67, para. 164</P1></P>
<P>17. Following the creation of his working paper, Mr. Kendal prepared his draft Prosecution Report. Despite being aware that Deborah Ferens could not say how many till tapes she was being provided with, in the draft Prosecution Report, Mr. Kendal wrote:
<QUOTE><P>Interviews with the bookkeeper will show that she only received two till tapes per day from the Samaroos, not the three that were actually produced in the normal course of the business day.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 28, para. 28</P1></P>
<P>18. Mr. Kendal also wrote that the respondents only provided 2 of the three till tapes per day to their bookkeeper, Ms. Ferens, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Debbie Ferens has stated to the auditor that she only ever received two till tapes from the Samaroos to do the books of MGM (see witness report #1 for the auditor Glen Foster). Debbie Ferens will be contacted and interviewed to confirm this statement. In addition she will be contacted to confirm if she received 3 till tapes per day during the 2007 fiscal period of MGM.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 28, para. 29</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>C.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Referral of the Draft Prosecution Report to PPSC and Creation of Draft Charge Approval Memorandum:</UNDER></TI>
<P>19. Mr. Kendal forwarded his draft Prosecution Report to Brian Jones, who in turn provided it to Lisa McLean at PPSC. Ms. McLean spoke with Brian Jones by telephone on January 7, 2008 and then with Mr. Kendal on January 10, 2008. She recorded in her notes of the call with Mr. Kendal that he told her:
<QUOTE><P>He can show he's got it; can't really show when earned it.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>20. And under a heading called &ldquo;Bkkpr&rdquo; she wrote:
<QUOTE><P>He has not interviewed her. She takes the z tapes and posts to spreadsheet.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. pp. 29, 30, paras. 34-35</P1></P>
<P>21. Mr. Kendal did not reference Ms. Ferens' second interview in his January 10, 2008 call with Ms. McLean.
<P1>A.R. p. 83, para. 217</P1></P>
<P>22. Ms. McLean prepared a draft charge approval memorandum dated January 14, 2008. The memorandum reflected her thought process and position following her review of the draft Prosecution Report and after consultation with Bruce Harper (her team leader at PPSC) and Jana Hyman (a colleague at PPSC). Both Mr. Harper and Ms. Hyman agreed with her views on the file.
<P1>A.R. p. 31, para. 40</P1></P>
<P>23. Ms. McLean's draft charge approval memorandum clearly states that while PPSC was of the view that charges were appropriate, they should not be approved until further investigative steps were taken, including an interview of Ms. Ferens. Ms. McLean then spoke to Mr. Kendal on January 14, 2008. In her notes she identifies the following necessary investigative steps to be completed before charges could be approved, which she communicated to Mr. Kendal:
<QUOTE><P>Interview bookkeeper
<P1>a) last person to see z tapes</P1>
<P1>b) what did they show date &amp; times. Breakdown by</P1>
<P1>c) what did she do</P1>
<P1>d) want to find out, did he supress night shift, different shifts, the cash from more than 1 shift</P1>
<P1>e) did both ts and hs deal with her. What were their roles</P1></P>
<P>He agreed with that. He will:
<P1>1) Will interview bookkeeper;</P1>
<P1>2) employees</P1>
<P1>3) Finish RTCC</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 32, para. 46</P1></P>
<P>24. As found by the trial judge, Ms. McLean was operating on the assumption, based on the information received from Mr. Kendal, that Ms. Ferens did see the till tapes and could confirm that not all income from the restaurants was being reported.
<P1>A.R. p. 33, para. 47</P1></P>
<P>25. It is significant that three senior lawyers within PPSC were of the opinion that no charges should be approved until the investigative tasks identified by Ms. McLean were completed, including the interview of Ms. Ferens.
<P1>A.R. p. 33, para. 49</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>D.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Completion of the Prosecution Report, Preparation of the Information and Charge Approval:</UNDER></TI>
<P>26. Mr. Kendal did not interview Ms. Ferens as directed by PPSC. He contacted Mr. Heese and Ms. Ferens to arrange an interview and was subsequently advised that all further requests for information should be directed through their counsel, Mr. George Jones.
<P1>A.R. p. 34, para. 52</P1></P>
<P>27. Mr. Kendal spoke again to Ms. McLean on February 11, 2008, and he told her that the bookkeeper did not want to be interviewed. He did not say that Ms. Ferens had agreed to answer questions through her counsel. He failed to disclose Mr. Finlay's interview or that Ms. Ferens had been clear that she could not provide evidence that a shift was unreported, or if that had been the case, which one.
<P1>A.R. p. 34, para. 54</P1></P>
<P>28. On March 20, 2008, the CRA provided PPSC with Mr. Kendal's final Prosecution Report, together with a covering letter which Mr. Kendal authored. The letter states that the CRA was alleging that the respondents appropriated $1,754,812.00 from their corporate businesses during the years 2004 to 2006. And that the sales belonging to the restaurant were suppressed by the respondents providing only two of three till tapes per day to their bookkeeper.
<P1>A.R. p. 34, para. 55</P1></P>
<P>29. In the final Prosecution Report, under the heading &ldquo;Part V&mdash;Theory of the Case&rdquo;, Mr. Kendal wrote:
<QUOTE><P>Scheme 1: Tony &amp; Helen Samaroo operated three regular shifts at the MGM restaurant and each shift produced a rung off till tape. The Samaroos under reported sales revenue &amp; the related GST from MGM Restaurants Ltd. by not providing one of the three daily till tapes to their bookkeeper resulting in a personal enrichment of about $50,000 per month.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 35, para. 56</P1></P>
<P>30. And, under &ldquo;Element 3&rdquo; of the CRA's theory of the case Mr. Kendal wrote:
<QUOTE><P>- The bookkeeper Debbie Ferens (witness #4), will be able to explain that she received a filled out preformatted &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; summary sheet for each day of the month with till tape #1 sales data, till tape #2 sales data and a summary column of those two days till tapes, and this is attached with the till tapes for that month as provided to her by Tony Samaroo...</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 35, para. 60</P1></P>
<P>31. And under &ldquo;Element 4&rdquo; Mr. Kendal wrote:
<QUOTE><P>Element #4: The accused provided only two of three daily till tapes to their bookkeeper Debbie Ferens to February 28, 2006.</P>
<P>- Deborah Ferens (witness #4) will be able to attest to having met the CRA auditor, Glen Foster on March 21st of 2006, and informed him that she has only ever received two MGM till tapes per day from Tony Samaroo for the period under audit.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 36, para. 61</P1></P>
<P>32. As found by the trial judge:
<QUOTE><P>[230] I conclude that despite what he said in his Prosecution Report, Mr. Kendal understood that the theory that only two till tapes were being reported could not be proved by the sales summary sheets and that Ms. Ferens could not testify to that. He clearly appreciated that the summary sheets could include information from three ring-offs or shifts. In his evidence he confirmed that he knew the daily sales summary sheet showed two columns of data but did not know how many till tapes it represented and in particular whether it represented two or three till tapes or shifts.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 87, para. 230</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>E.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Drafting of the Information and Charge Approval:</UNDER></TI>
<P>33. The trial judge found that the charges against the respondents were not &lsquo;approved&rsquo; until June 2008, when Keith Kendal swore the 21-count Information. Neither Ms. Jana Hyman nor Mr. Jones prepared any written analysis of the case nor did the two ever discuss the legal reasoning of the case. Mr. Kendal drafted the information and swore it, without the final draft having been reviewed by anyone within PPSC or Mr. Brian Jones. Ms. Hyman and Mr. Jones relied on Keith Kendal to gather the evidence, draft the final Information, and essentially, do charge approval.
<P1>A.R. p. 74, para. 193, and p. 75, paras. 195&ndash;197</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>F.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>2010 Interviews of Deborah Ferens and Diane Ye:</UNDER></TI>
<P>34. It is critical to note that the appellant makes no mention in their statement of facts of Mr. Kendal's 2010 interviews of Ms. Ferens and Ms. Ye nor do they challenge the trial judge's findings of fact in relation to these matters.</P>
<P>35. In early 2010, Mr. Brian Jones instructed Keith Kendal to interview Ms. Ferens again. Mr. Kendal prepared 41 pages of questions before that interview, which took place on January 22, 2010. The questions have the appearance of Mr. Kendal seeking to obtain from Ms. Ferens the evidence he wanted from her and had already attributed to her.
<P1>A.R. p. 64, para. 154</P1></P>
<P>36. Ms. Ferens told Mr. Kendal that she thought (assumed) that the daily sales summary sheet had two columns (day and night) because it reflected information from two shifts, but she repeated what she had told Mr. Finlay on January 24, 2007, which is that she never looked at the supporting till tapes and could not say how many, or which ones, she received.
<P1>A.R. p. 65, para. 155</P1></P>
<P>37. The will-say statement of Deborah Ferens' January 22, 2010 interview was typed up on February 9, 2010. Then, on February 16, 2010, Mr. Kendal interviewed Diane Ye for the third time. It is significant that in her first two interviews, she states that she received a single daily sales summary sheet, and that the summary sheet columns were labelled &ldquo;day&rdquo; and &ldquo;night&rdquo;. Not, &ldquo;till tape #1&rdquo; and &ldquo;till tape #2&rdquo; as Mr. Kendal had written in the Prosecution Report.
<P1>A.R. p. 65, paras. 156&ndash;158</P1></P>
<P>38. During the third interview of Ms. Ye, she is recorded as having said, for the first time, that she actually received two daily sales summary sheets. One for the &lsquo;day&rsquo; and &lsquo;night&rsquo; shifts, and a separate sheet used solely for the &lsquo;graveyard&rsquo; shift.
<P1>A.R. p. 65,66, paras. 159&ndash;161.</P1></P>
<P>39. Mr. Kendal testified that the first time the existence of a second daily sales summary sheet entered his mind was when it was disclosed by Ms. Ye during her third interview. While the interview notes of Ms. Ferens' interview show she was never asked about a second sheet, her will say states that she only ever received one sheet. Mr. Kendal explained that after he was told about a second sheet by Diane Ye, he went back and altered Ms. Ferens' will-say to include the corroborative statement that she only received a single sheet. As the trial judge found: &ldquo;Mr. Kendal seemed to think this was perfectly acceptable&rdquo;.
<P1>A.R. p. 66, para. 162</P1></P>
<P>40. Surprisingly, the appellant describes Mr. Kendal's actions in manufacturing evidence and attributing it to Deborah Ferens as &ldquo;not an advisable practice&rdquo;, but they go on to say that in any event, it did not matter because the evidence was &lsquo;not material&rsquo;: appellant's factum, p. 29, para. 97.</P>
<P>41. The trial judge took a different view. He found that Mr. Kendal hoped that if he interviewed Ms. Ferens for a third time, he could obtain the evidence from her that he had already wrongfully attributed to her in the Prosecution Report. It was clear that he anticipated getting her to say that she only got two till tapes for each day. The trial judge also found that Mr. Kendal's approach to his interview of Ms. Ferens was telling, given he had earlier misreported that Ms. Ferens had refused to be interviewed. The trial judge found: &ldquo;I conclude that it was important to him to interview her personally as he sought to support the evidence he had attributed to her throughout&rdquo;.
<P1>A.R. pp. 85-86, paras. 221&ndash;226</P1></P>
<P>42. On March 3, 2010, Mr. Kendal provided copies of both the will-say statements of Ms. Ye and Ms. Ferens to Brian Jones, and Mr. Jones testified he probably reviewed them that day. His time sheet entries show that he spent 1.5 hours reviewing the documents and speaking to Mr. Kendal about them.
<P1>A.R. p. 67, paras. 163 and 166.</P1></P>
<P>43. Although Mr. Kendal had been responsible for disclosure throughout the prosecution, he did not disclose the will-say statements to the respondents. For reasons that were not explained, he testified that the decision to disclose them rested with Mr. Jones because they were the Crown's &lsquo;property&rsquo;. In fact, the will-say statements of Ms. Ferens and Ms. Ye were not disclosed to the respondents until the second day of the criminal trial, and only after the Crown was ordered to provide particulars of the overt acts of evasion being alleged against the respondents.
<P1>A.R. p. 67, para. 164</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>G.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>The Criminal Trial:</UNDER></TI>
<P>44. The criminal trial began on September 20, 2010.Mr. Jones outlined the Crown's case and told the criminal trial judge that theory of the Crown was that the respondents were providing only two of the three daily till tapes to their bookkeeper, Ms. Ferens. He told the court: &ldquo;... the bookkeeper until the audit is announced receives only two ring offs each day prior to the audit&rdquo;. No mention is made of Ms. Ye's evidence in relation to the supposed existence of a second daily sales summary sheet.
<P1>A.R. p. 68, paras. 170, 171</P1></P>
<P>45. Following the Crown's opening, the respondents applied for particulars of what the Crown was alleging were the overt acts of evasion. The criminal trial judge ordered particulars, which the Crown provided the next day. The trial judge found that those particulars did no more than repeat what the Crown had put forward as its theory based on missing till tapes; it did not particularize the overt acts.
<P1>A.R. p. 70, paras. 176,177</P1></P>
<P>46. Immediately after filing the particulars, the Crown disclosed, for the first time, the will-say statements of the 2010 interviews of Ms. Ferens and Ms. Ye.
<P1>A.R. p. 70, para. 178</P1></P>
<P>47. The following day, the respondents again applied for further particulars. In the course of resisting the application, Mr. Jones told the court as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The position of the Crown is and always has been that it's Mr. Samaroo giving these [sic] only two till tapes instead of three to Ms. Ferens, the bookkeeper, knowing that that raw data will be transferred into a monthly sales statement, monthly revenue statement, that will be transferred into an annual revenue statement, which will find its way into eventually a tax return. That's always been the Crown's position. That's always been what this disclosure previously has been about.</P>
<P>[183] Mr. Jones then read from the Prosecution Report:</P>
<P>Now, I have a theory as to how they did it and that theory&mdash;that theory was put in writing, in black and white, in the Crown brief that was given to defence at or about the first appearance in court of Mr. Samaroo. That was years ago. Can I just read, if I may, from the Crown brief that was given to defence. Part 5, theory of the case. And for my friends' benefit, it's at page six of 50 of Tab 1, binder F, the prosecution report. Part 5, theory of the case [as read in]:
<QUOTE><P>Scheme 1. Tony and Helen Samaroo operated three regular shifts at the M.G.M. Restaurant and each shift produced a rung-off till tape. The Samaroos under-reported sales revenue and the related GST from M.G.M. Restaurants Limited by not providing one of the three daily till tapes to their bookkeeper, resulting in a personal enrichment of about $50,000 per month.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>The theory of the Crown, black and white, given to defence years ago. So it's not just me standing on my two feet today, Your Honour, stating what the theory is. Always been the theory.</P>
<P>And that theory&mdash;that Scheme 1 is then broken down into various elements, talking about what we understood people were doing. But the theory's always been there.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 71/72, paras. 182, 183</P1></P>
<P>48. However, in his closing submissions before the criminal trial judge, Mr. Jones made no mention of Ms. Ferens' unreported till tape theory&mdash;the Crown's position, in &lsquo;black and white&rsquo;, for the previous two years&mdash;instead taking the position, for the first time, that the overt act of evasion now being alleged by the Crown was based on Diane Ye's &lsquo;missing second sheet&rsquo; theory.
<P1>A.R. p. 96, 97, paras.266&ndash;268</P1></P>
<P>49. When asked to described how it could be that Mr. Samaroo had committed the overt acts, Mr. Jones explained it was &ldquo;magic&rdquo;.
<P1>A.R. p. 97, para. 267</P1></P>
<P>50. On April 6, 2011, the respondents were acquitted of all charges.</P>
<P>51. While the trial judge did not find Mr. Jones liable for malicious prosecution, and the respondents accept that finding, the trial judge did find that Mr. Jones' failure to fulfill all of his obligations as Crown caused him to give up control of the prosecution to Mr. Kendal and the CRA, and in doing so, risked a miscarriage of justice.
<P1>A.R. p. 101, para. 281.</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ISSUES ON APPEAL</TI>
<P>52. The appellant raises four issues on this appeal, as follows:
<P1>a. That the trial judge erred in law in holding that the manner of fraud and the quantum of unreported income were necessary elements of proof of the offence of tax evasion;</P1>
<P1>b. That the trial judge erred in law by requiring the appellant to prove the <EM>actus reus</EM> of tax evasion in order to establish reasonable and probable cause;</P1>
<P1>c. That the trial judge erred in law in finding that the circumstances known to the Crown prosecutor at the relevant time could not establish reasonable and probable cause to commence a prosecution; and,</P1>
<P1>d. That the trial judge erred in fact and in law in finding that the CRA investigator supressed or withheld materiel evidence from the Crown and that he was therefore motivated by malice.</P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The respondents' position in respect to the points in issue on this appeal:</EM></TI>
<P>53. Issues 1, 2, and 3, all relate to the third element of the tort of malicious prosecution: the existence of reasonable and probable cause to initiate or continue the prosecution against the respondents. The trial judge made no error of law in finding that reasonable and probable cause did not exist. He correctly set out the law in respect to the tort of malicious prosecution, and in respect to tax evasion. The trial judge correctly applied the law to the facts in finding that the charges against the respondents were founded on an assumption, and grounded in mere suspicion and hypotheses, which did not and could not constitute reasonable and probable cause as that term is uniquely defined in the tort of malicious prosecution.</P>
<P>54. Issue 4 relates to the trial judge's finding that Mr. Kendal was motivated by malice. The trial judge correctly found that Mr. Kendal acted deliberately to supress evidence and attribute evidence to witnesses that was not accurate. The trial judge correctly found that Mr. Kendal decided from the beginning that the Samaroos were guilty and set out to prove that was the case even if doing so required a breach of his proper role and responsibilities.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>A.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Standard of Review:</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. Issues 1, 2, and 3 are questions of law reviewable on a correctness standard.</P>
<P>56. Issue 4 is described by the appellant as involving an error in law and in fact. The appellant takes the position that there was &lsquo;no evidence&rsquo; and there were &lsquo;no grounds&rsquo; for a finding of malice in respect to Mr. Kendal: appellant's factum, p. 28, para. 92. There is no dispute that it is an error of law to make a finding of fact for which there is no supporting evidence: <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. J.M.H.</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 45 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>57. The respondents submit that while the appellant is seeking to couch their objection as a question of law, in effect the appellant takes issue with the trial judge's assessment of the significant volume of evidence tendered in relation to the issue of whether Mr. Kendal was motiviated by malice, and so the standard of palpable and overriding error applies.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>B.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Issues 1, 2, and 3:</UNDER></TI>
<P>58. Issues 1, 2, and 3 all relate to the trial judge's findings of law in respect to the third element of the tort of malicious prosecution, and are dealt with together in the respondents' factum.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The trial judge correctly determined that there was no reasonable and probable cause to initiate or continue the prosecution:</EM></TI>
<P>59. At para. 130 of his reasons, the trial judge correctly summarized the law in relation to the issue of &lsquo;reasonable and probable cause&rsquo; as set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Miazga:</EM>
<QUOTE><P>[130] However the proper test for reasonable and probable grounds to be applied to the tort of malicious prosecution is as summarized by the Supreme Court in <EM>Miazga</EM>:</P>
<P>a) The tort of malicious prosecution &ldquo;targets the decision to initiate or continue with a criminal prosecution&rdquo; (para. 6);</P>
<P>b) The tort of malicious prosecution is &ldquo;designed to provide redress for losses flowing from an unjustified prosecution&rdquo; (para. 42);</P>
<P>c) The elements of the tort are the same no matter the parties: para. 44;</P>
<P>d) The &ldquo;initiation&rdquo; requirement identifies the appropriate target of the suit: para. 53.</P>
<P>e) <UNDER>Given the burden of proof in a criminal trial, &ldquo;probable guilt&rdquo; means that, on an objective assessment, based on the existing state of circumstances, proof beyond a reasonable doubt could be made out in a court of law: para. 63.</UNDER></P>
<P>f) Reasonable and probable cause is a question of law to be decided by the judge: para. 74. This means that the subjective state of mind of the defendants is not a relevant consideration hence there is no unfairness in applying the same test to both an investigator and prosecutor. The question is whether the prosecution was properly initiated.</P>
<P>g) There is no &ldquo;sliding scale&rdquo; for reasonable and probable cause depending on who the defendants are. The test is the same in any public prosecution.</P>
<P>h) If the court determines that no objective grounds existed for the prosecution at the relevant time then the court must consider the fourth element, that of malice: para. 77.
<P1>[Emphasis added]</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 54/55. para. 130</P1></P>
<P>60. With respect, the issue of reasonable and probable cause is straightforward. The appellant and Crown alleged that the respondents' evaded tax in 2004 and 2005, by providing only 2 of the 3 daily till tapes to their bookkeeper, Deborah Ferens. The evidence of Deborah Ferens was necessary to prove the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offences. Without her evidence, reasonable and probable cause did not exist to initiate the prosecution. The position taken by PPSC and communicated to Mr. Kendal was that absent Ms. Ferens' evidence, charges could not be approved. Her evidence was essential to prove that the funds in question were unreported income earned during the period of the Information. As the trial judge correctly found, Deborah Ferens' evidence could not prove the <EM>actus reus</EM>. She had no idea how many till tapes she was being provided with or what information was represented in the daily sales summary sheet. All she knew was that the sheet contained three columns: one labelled &lsquo;day&rsquo;, one labelled &lsquo;night&rsquo; and one labelled &lsquo;days total&rsquo;. As such, there was no reasonable and probable cause to initiate the prosecution. Mr. Kendal knew this from the outset of his investigation. Rather than admit it, he set out to manufacture a case against the respondents to ensure charge approval and prosecution. In doing so he created evidence in relation to Deborah Ferens that he knew did not exist and actively suppressed her actual evidence, given to Mr. Finlay, from the PPSC to ensure charges were approved.</P>
<P>61. It is submitted that the trial judge was correct in finding that there was no reasonable and probable cause to initiate the prosecution, which he summarized as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[244] To summarize, the defendants had no evidence to prove, and knew they could not prove, whether the plaintiffs were providing only two of the three till tapes to Ms. Ferens, or which of the three till tapes. This meant they could not prove the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offence of tax evasion, nor could they ever hope to prove the quantum of the evasion. As in <EM>Proulx</EM>, the charges against the Samaroos were founded on an assumption, and grounded in mere suspicion and hypotheses, which did not and could not constitute reasonable and probable cause as that term is uniquely defined in the tort of malicious prosecution.</P>
<P>[245] This prosecution should never have proceeded. It was undertaken without reasonable and probable cause. The third element required by <EM>Miazga</EM> is satisfied as against all defendants.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 90, paras. 244,245</P1></P>
<P>62. The merits of the other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; pointed to by the appellant as being capable of establishing reasonable and probable cause must be considered bearing in mind that Mr. Kendal's investigation of the respondents was tainted from the outset.</P>
<P>63. The trial judge found that Mr. Kendal did not start from a neutral position and then undertake an objective investigation. He saw his investigative task to be discrediting the respondents' explanation of the source of funds. From the outset, Mr. Kendal rejected the explanations of Mr. Samaroo and Mr. Heese for the accumulation of cash. He started out with the assumption that the deposits and cash payments were made with suppressed income skimmed from the businesses. And, Mr. Kendal set out, not to conduct an impartial investigation, but to in his own words, &lsquo;deflect the defence of a lifetime of savings&rsquo; and to &lsquo;defuse the Defence position&rsquo;. The appellant does not challenge these findings.</P>
<P>64. Kendal could prove the respondents had the money, but he knew he could not prove whether it was skimmed, when it was skimmed, how it was skimmed, or from which business. Mr. Kendal developed a theory to explain the source of the deposits&mdash;that the respondents were not providing one daily till tape to their bookkeeper. But, as he admitted in his &ldquo;Investigations Plan&mdash;MGM&rdquo;, he knew from the beginning he could not prove that one shift was not being reported to Deborah Ferens in 2004 and 2005. Mr. Kendal knew that Deborah Ferens could not and would not testify that she only received 2 till tapes per day.</P>
<P>65. When Mr. Kendal created his draft and final Prosecution Reports, he did so knowing that the Crown would rely on the information he provided to determine whether the prosecution would proceed. Bear in mind that at the same time Kendal prepared the other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; in the draft and final Prosecution Reports, he was actively suppressing the Finlay interview from PPSC and manufacturing evidence that he attributed to Ms. Ferens. It is respectfully submitted that he was also engaging in what judge Saunders called &lsquo;voodoo&rsquo; accounting. He created hundreds of working papers, based on faulty extrapolations and assumptions&mdash;coming to entirely different results than Glen Foster&mdash;in an attempt to explain the source of the deposits and cash payments. This was an attempt to build a case and secure a conviction. These purported other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; are merely a part of Mr. Kendal's continuing efforts to manufacture a case against the respondents, used to prop up the evidence he manufactured and attributed to Deborah Ferens&mdash;when he knew that he could not prove the third shift was not being reported from the beginning of the investigation.</P>
<P>66. Mr. Kendal's own views of the merits of his other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; is revealed by his treatment of Ms. Ferens' &lsquo;evidence&rsquo; in his dealings with PPSC and in his reports, and confirmed by his approach to the 2010 interviews of Ms. Ferens and Ms. Ye. Mr. Kendal knew that Ms. Ferens' evidence was necessary to prove the offences, and he was told in no uncertain terms by PPSC that without confirmation of her testimony, there would be insufficient evidence to support charge approval. Instead of pointing out to PPSC the other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; that he included in his prosecution reports as an alternative basis upon which charges could be approved, he instead went to great lengths to suppress the Finlay interview from PPSC; he created evidence and attributed it to Ms. Ferens; and, he misled Lisa McLean about Ms. Ferens' willingness to be interviewed.</P>
<P>67. Perhaps the most critical evidence confirming the lack of reasonable and probable cause to proceed with the prosecution is found in the notes of Ms. McLean of her telephone call with Mr. Kendal on January 10, 2008 where she wrote what Kendal told her about the sufficiency of the evidence:
<QUOTE><P>He can show he's got it; can't really show when earned it.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 29, para. 34</P1></P>
<P>68. What Ms. McLean did not know was that Deborah Ferens had at this point already been interviewed by Mr. Finlay and had confirmed that she could not provide the evidence that Mr. Kendal had already wrongfully attributed to her. Ms. McLean was led to believe that Ms. Ferens had yet to be interviewed as part of the investigation, and it was a simple matter of Mr. Kendal &lsquo;confirming&rsquo; her evidence to Mr. Foster that she only ever received two till tapes per day during the period in question. Of course, she had not said that. Mr. Kendal had created that evidence and attributed it to her.</P>
<P>69. Further, as found by the trial judge, the appellant's position on this appeal&mdash;that Ms. Ferens' evidence was immaterial to proving the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offences&mdash;is inconsistent with the testimony of the appellant's own witnesses and of Lisa McLean. It is directly contrary to Ms. McLean's position taken on behalf of PPSC in her draft charge approval memorandum (the only written legal analysis ever prepared by the Crown) which was agreed to and adopted by Jana Hyman and Bruce Harper at PPSC. And, it is inconsistent with the basis upon which charges were approved and upon which the prosecution was initiated and proceeded to trial.</P>
<P>70. The trial judge was entitled to rely on the evidence led by the appellant at trial, on the contents of the prosecution report, and on the evidence of Lisa McLean, that the <EM>actus reus</EM> or overt acts of the alleged offences was that the respondents were providing only 2 of 3 till tapes to Deborah Ferens during the period of the offences, and that Deborah Ferens' evidence was necessary to prove the <EM>actus reus</EM> of the offences. With respect, it is not open to the appellant to effectively attempt to impeach its own witnesses on this appeal.</P>
<P>71. Further, even if this court were to turn a blind eye to Mr. Kendal's conduct and the unchallenged context in which the other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; were created, reasonable and probable cause is not made out. As found by the trial judge, even if the other facts give rise to a suspicion: &ldquo;it comes no where near meeting the evidentiary requirement of proving that within the alleged time frame the money was skimmed from the restaurant. It is a theory, a suspicion, and convictions are not entered on theories or suspicions&rdquo;. A.R. p. 81, para. 207.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The trial judge applied the correct legal principles and did not reverse the onus of proof in respect to reasonable and probable cause:</EM></TI>
<P>72. The trial judge's decision comprises 102 pages and 340 paragraphs. He thoroughly canvassed the evidence, clearly set out his findings of fact, correctly set out the relevant legal principles, and then carefully and considerately applied the law to the facts. At paragraphs 98&ndash;105 of his reasons (A.R. pp. 46&ndash;48), the trial judge correctly set out the law in relation to tax evasion and noted that the obligation on the Crown was to prove both the <EM>mens rea</EM> and <EM>actus reus</EM> of the alleged offences beyond a reasonable doubt. And, the trial judge correctly set out the law in relation to the issue of reasonable and probable cause&mdash;the third element of the tort of malicious prosecution&mdash;at paragraphs 117 to 130 of his reasons (A.R. pp. 51&ndash;54).</P>
<P>73. With respect, when the trial judge's findings in relation to reasonable and probable cause are read in the context of the reasons as a whole, it is apparent that he understood and applied the correct legal principles including the correct onus of proof.</P>
<P>74. By pointing out that the criminal trial judge rejected most, if not all of the other &lsquo;facts&rsquo; suggested by the appellant, and noting that the appellant did not prove any of those facts during the trial, the trial judge was merely highlighting the obvious defiencies of the &lsquo;other facts&rsquo;. The trial judge was alive to the fact that Mr. Kendal included those calculations and conclusions in his report not in the capacity of an objective investigator, but as an advocate determined to manufacture a case against the respondents and ensure charge approval and prosecution. A reading of the trial judge's reasons as a whole make it apparent that the trial judge found on the evidence that the respondent's had proved an absence of reasonable and probable cause.</P>
<P>75. Further, the trial judge's reference to the lack of any explanation as to how Helen Samaroo was involved in the alleged scheme of evasion is correct. At no point during the prosecution of the respondents or during the malicious prosecution trial was an explanation ever offered as to how Mrs. Samaroo may have been involved in allegedly supressing information from Deborah Ferens. Lisa McLean states in her draft charge approval memorandum that in her view, on behalf of PPSC, Helen Samaroo should not be charged with either corporate evasion or personal evasion:
<QUOTE><P>A.B. pp. 63 (bottom third) and 64 (bottom third). No other written legal analysis of the merits of proceeding against Mrs. Samaroo was ever created.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><UNDER>C.</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Issue 4:</UNDER></TI>
<P>76. The appellant alleges that the trial judge erred in fact and in law in finding that Mr. Kendal suppressed or withheld material evidence from the Crown, and that he was therefore motivated by malice.</P>
<P>77. First, the appellant is mistaken in suggesting that the trial judge's finding of malice in relation to Mr. Kendal was based only on the fact that Mr. Kendal suppressed evidence (appellant's factum, p. 22, para. 69). The trial judge found, at paragraph 247 of his reasons (A.R. p. 91) that from the inception of Mr. Kendal's investigation he rejected outright the explanations provided by Mr. Samaroo about the source of the cash deposits. Mr. Kendal created a working paper shortly after the execution of the search warrants in which he sets out his plan to &ldquo;deflect the defence of a lifetime of savings&rdquo; and &ldquo;defuse&rdquo; the respondents' position. The trial judge correctly found that Mr. Kendal:
<QUOTE><P>...had his mind made up from the beginning and set out to have the plaintiffs charged and convicted. His sole interest was to collect incriminating evidence and to discount or ignore evidence that did not support his prejudgment. He saw his investigative task as not to fairly examine and report the evidence of the plaintiffs but instead to discredit it.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 91, para. 247</P1></P>
<P>78. It is critical to note that the appellant does not challenge this finding of the trial judge. Nor does the appellant challenge the trial judge's finding that Mr. Kendal began with the deposits of cash and worked backwards in an attempt to develop a theory of how the tax evasion had occurred.</P>
<P>79. The appellant makes reference to various statements in the final Prosecution Report that they say are proof Mr. Kendal &lsquo;disclosed&rsquo; the contents of the Finlay interview of Ms. Ferens. They say, essentially, that the fact Ms. Ferens had no idea how many till tapes she received and could not testify to that fact is &lsquo;specifically noted&rsquo; or &lsquo;can be inferred&rsquo;. It is manifestly clear that Mr. Kendal created evidence which he attributed to Ms. Ferens, and suppressed her true evidence from the PPSC, the Crown, and the respondents. Mr. Kendal made no mention of the Finlay interview in his testimony during the criminal trial, and in the malicious prosecution trial, he continued his efforts to suppress this evidence. He testified in direct that in preparing the Prosecution Reports, he relied wholly on Ms. Ferens' statement to Glen Foster: A.R. p. 86, paras. 227 and 228 and made no reference to the Finlay interview, despite admitting in cross that he had reviewed Finlay's notes the week prior. The appellant does not challenge the finding of the trial judge that Mr. Kendal attempted to conceal the existence of the Finlay interview in his testimony before the trial judge: A.R. p. 92, paras. 252 and 253.</P>
<P>80. The appellant does not challenge the trial judge's finding that Mr. Kendal misled Lisa McLean by telling her the bookkeeper had yet to be interviewed on the issue of her only receiving two till tapes (which she had), and about whether she had refused to be interviewed by Mr. Kendal (she had not): A.R. p. 92, para. 250&ndash;252.</P>
<P>81. The appellant does not challenge the findings of the trial judge in respect to Mr. Kendal's credibility. Namely, that Mr. Kendal was argumentative, evasive, inflexible and reluctant to concede what clearly should have been conceded: A.R. p. 93, para. 258.</P>
<P>82. The appellant goes so far as to suggest: &ldquo;there is no evidence that Mr. Kendal suppressed key information and thereby misled the prosecutors&rdquo; (appellant's factum, p. 22, para. 70). With respect, this assertion is manifestly incorrect. The trial judge found that Mr. Kendal clearly withheld evidence from and misled PPSC, based on the following findings of fact which are not challenged by the appellant:
<P1>a. Mr. Kendal knew that Ms. Ferens' had told Mr. Finlay that she did not look at the till tapes and did not know and could not say how many till tapes she received from the respondents, nor what information it represented: A.R. p. 26, para. 24;</P1>
<P1>b. Despite that knowledge, Mr. Kendal wrote in the draft Prosecution Report that:
<QUOTE><P>interviews with the bookkeeper will show that she only received two till tapes per day from the Samaroos: A.R p. 28, para. 28;</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>c. And:
<QUOTE><P>Debbie Ferens has stated to the auditor that she only ever received two till tapes from the Samaroos to do the books of MGM (see witness report #1 for the auditor Glen Foster). Debbie Ferens will be contacted and interviewed to confirm this statement;</P></QUOTE>
<P2>A.R. p. 28, para. 29</P2></P1>
<P1>d. Mr. Kendal did not disclose the existence of the Finlay interview to Ms. McLean, even after he was directed to interview Ms. Ferens and confirm her evidence that she only received 2 daily till taps A.R. p. 64, para. 152;</P1>
<P1>e. Mr. Kendal misled Ms. McLean when he told her that Ms. Ferens' had refused to be interviewed. She had not refused, just requested that questions be put through her counsel, Mr. George Jones: A.R. p. 34, para. 54</P1>
<P1>f. Mr. Kendal prepared the final Prosecution Report and charges were &lsquo;approved&rsquo; on the theory that during 2004-2005 the Samaroos appropriated $1.7 million from their businesses by failing to report one of the three daily till tapes. He included these critical passages in the Prosecution Report in respect to Ms. Ferens, which also served as her will-say statement because no will-say was prepared:
<QUOTE><P>The bookkeeper Debbie Ferens...will be able to explain that she received a filled out preformatted &ldquo;Daily Cash Report&rdquo; summary sheet for each day of the month with till tape #1 sales data, till tape #2 sales data and a summary column of those two days till tapes, and this is attached with the till tapes for that month as provided to her by Tony Samaroo.</P>
<P>And:
<QUOTE><P>Element #4: The accused provided only two of the three daily till tapes to their bookkeeper Debbie Ferens to February 28, 2006.</P>
<P>- Debbie Ferens will be able to attest to having met the CRA auditor, Glen Foster on March 21st of 2006, and informed him that <UNDER>she has only ever received two MGM till tapes per day from Tony Samaroo for the period under audit</UNDER>. [Emphasis added.] A.R. p. 83, para. 216</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>g. Mr. Kendal chose not to prepare a will-say statement for Ms. Ferens nor did he disclose the notes of the Finlay interview in the witness statement binder disclosed to the respondents. Instead, he buried it in a large binder of search materials&mdash;one of 88 binders of disclosure&mdash;and made no reference to the notes in the index of the binder: (A.R. p. 64, para. 153).</P1>
<P1>h. In 2010, Mr. Kendal was directed to interview Ms. Ferens. He prepared 41 pages of typed questions before that interview which had the appearance of Mr. Kendal seeking to obtain from Ms. Ferens the evidence he wanted from her and had already wrongfully attributed to her: (A.R. p. 64, para. 154);</P1>
<P1>i. After typing up Ms. Ferens' will-say on February 9, 2010, Mr. Kendal interviewed Ms. Diane Ye for the third time, during which she mentioned for the first time the alleged existence of a &lsquo;second&rsquo; daily sales summary sheet. Then, Mr. Kendal went back and altered Ms. Ferens' will-say to include the corroborative statement that she only received one sheet from the respondents. Mr. Kendal did not disclose to the respondents either the 2010 interviews of Ms. Ferens or Ms. Ye, despite having been responsible for disclosure up until that point. A.R. p. 64, see discussion on disclosure issues</P1></P>
<P>83. As found by the trial judge:
<QUOTE><P>[62] Knowing that he had not carried out the investigatory steps requested by Ms. McLean, and knowing that Ms. Ferens could not provide evidence proving that only two till tapes from two shifts were reported, Mr. Kendal nonetheless proceeded and in doing so provided incomplete and erroneous information to those who would rely upon and act upon this Prosecution Report. They did so and the matter proceeded to charge approval.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 36, para. 62</P1></P>
<P>84. As the appellant states at p. 25, paras. 79 and 80 of their factum, the PPSC &lsquo;necessarily&rsquo; depended on Mr. Kendal for the information upon which the prosecution was approved and proceeded. It was Mr. Kendal who, through his &lsquo;summary of available evidence&rsquo; in the form of his two Prosecution Reports, identified &lsquo;what evidence supports the charges&rsquo;. As Ms. McLean testified, and as the appellant points out, PPSC relied on Mr. Kendal for the information he provided in respect to Ms. Ferens in order to determine if charges would go forward. As found by the trial judge, and not challenged by the appellant, Mr. Kendal was clearly &lsquo;actively&rsquo; instrumental in the prosecution of the respondents. He caused everything to be done which could be done to wrongfully set the law in motion against the Samaroos. As found by the trial judge (A.R. p. 75, para. 198), CRA initiated the prosecution within the meaning of the tort of malicious prosecution, a finding not challenged by the appellant on this appeal.</P>
<P>85. The appellant makes reference to Brian Jones' and Janna Hyman's testimony at trial that they reviewed the Prosecution Report and held the view that the prosecution was &lsquo;justified&rsquo;. The trial judge weighed this evidence and importantly, found that neither Ms. Hyman or Mr. Jones ever prepared a written analysis of the case. Ms. Hyman had no record of ever having communicated her view to Mr. Jones and he testified that he had no discussions with Ms. Hyman about the legal reasoning behind the charges being laid: A.R. p. 38, para. 67.</P>
<P>86. Consider as well the trial judge's findings that Ms. Hyman and Mr. Jones' testimony in respect to when charges were approved and their respective roles in the charge approval process was directly contrary to the evidence: A.R. p. 73, para. 186.</P>
<P>87. In respect to the roles that Ms. Hyman, Mr. Jones and Mr. Kendal played in the charge approval process, the trial judge correctly concluded as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[195] Instead, I find that the charges against the Samaroos were not approved until Mr. Kendal swore the Information in June 2008. This means that in the charge approval process, neither Ms. Hyman, nor Mr. Brian Jones, prepared any written analysis of the case nor did the two ever discuss the legal reasoning of the case. Instead, it appears they relied on Mr. Kendal and the CRA to gather the evidence, draft the final Information, and essentially, do charge approval. While Mr. Jones approved the charges proceeding, it appears the extent of his actual contribution to charge approval was determining whether to proceed summarily or by indictment.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 75, para. 195</P1></P>
<P>88. The appellants take issue with the trial judge's findings that Mr. Kendal was &lsquo;in effect responsible for the prosecution of the Respondent and not the Crown&rsquo;: appellant's factum, p. 24, para. 76. Curiously, the appellant has not challenged the trial judge's finding that the CRA initiated the prosecution within the meaning of the tort of malicious prosecution. As set out above, the evidence was clear that Mr. Kendal was &lsquo;actively&rsquo; instrumental in setting the law in motion and as a result the appellant &lsquo;initiated&rsquo; the prosecution within the meaning of the tort of malicious prosecution.</P>
<P>89. It is significant to note that the appellant ignores the trial judge's extensive discussion on charge approval: A.R., pp. 72&ndash;75, paras. 185&ndash;195 and his findings of fact in respect to the charge approval process: A.R. pp. 36&ndash;43, paras. 63&ndash;87. It is critical to understand that the trial judge expressly found that Ms. Hyman and Mr. Jones' testimony as to when charges were approved was in direct contradiction to the evidence: A.R. p. 73, para. 186. The trial judge found that neither Ms. Hyman or Mr. Jones ever discussed the legal reasoning of the case nor did they prepare any written analysis of the case: A.R. p. 75, para. 195. The extent of Mr. Jones' actual contribution to charge approval was in respect to determining whether to proceed summarily or by indictment: A.R. p. 75, para. 195. In that regard, he emailed Ms. Hyman on April 29, 2008 and indicated, in favour of proceeding by indictment, that: &ldquo;on the other hand, getting serious time on one of these prosecutions is a goal I have yet to achieve&rdquo;: A.R. p. 40, para. 72. Mr. Jones explained in his examination for discovery and at trial that he was referring to his previous inability to &ldquo;have a court&rdquo; impose the sentence suggested by PPSC: A.R. p. 41, para. 73.</P>
<P>90. Critically, the trial judge found that Ms. McLean's position, taken on behalf of PPSC and set out in her draft memorandum on charge approval, was agreed to by both Jana Hyman and Bruce Harper. The trial judge found:
<QUOTE><P>[49] Three senior lawyers in the PPSC were of the opinion that no charges should be approved until the above tasks were completed. In addition, the amounts the corporations were to be charged with were to be calculated on a specific basis.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 33, para. 49.</P1></P>
<P>91. The appellant's frame one of the trial judge's findings in respect to Mr. Kendal's state of mind as follows: &ldquo;The trial judge found that Mr. Kendal acted with an improper purpose as he hoped to convict the Respondents because he believed they were guilty...Thus, Punnett J. accepted that Mr. Kendal believed in the respondents' guilt and that his purpose was to bring them before a criminal court for trial&rdquo;: A.R. p. 27, para. 86. The appellant relies on the finding for the proposition that a subjective belief in guilt will insulate a person from a malicious prosecution.</P>
<P>92. With respect, the appellant has materially misstated the trial judge's finding. The finding referred to is para. 257 of the trial judge's reasons, which provides as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[257] Proof of malice requires proof on a balance of probabilities that in the role of an investigator, Mr. Kendal acted deliberately to subvert and abuse his office. I find that he did so. He did so by supressing evidence and attributing evidence to witnesses that was not accurate. He had decided from the beginning of his involvement with the Samaroos that they were guilty and set out to prove that was the case even if to do so required a breach of his proper role and responsibilities. He knowingly misstated evidence essential to the proof of the <EM>actus reus</EM> despite being aware of its importance, filed a misleading report knowing it would be relied upon to authorize the prosecution and then having achieved that end swore the Information all in the hope of convicting the plaintiffs. His purpose was improper. I am satisfied that malice has been vicariously established as against the CRA as a result of the conduct of Mr. Kendal.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 93.</P1></P>
<P>93. And, the trial judge continued at para. 258 as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[258] As a witness, I found Mr. Kendal to be argumentative, evasive, inflexible and reluctant to concede what clearly should have been conceded. He wrote the Prosecution Report as an advocate not an investigator. He presented the evidence in a way designed to mislead both the PPSC and Mr. Brian Jones. His clear intent was to see that criminal charges were laid. The presumption of innocence appeared to be meaningless to him. The manner in which he approached the evidence was not objective. He had his theory and he then sought to prove it.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>A.R. p. 93</P1></P>
<P>94. It is clear that the trial judge did not accept that Mr. Kendal held a <EM>bona fide</EM>, honest belief in the guilt of the respondents. The Court in <EM>Miazga</EM> found that proof of malice requires that the respondent prove that the defendant was acting pursuant to an improper purpose inconsistent with his role: at para. 79. The trial judge applied the correct test and found that Mr. Kendal deliberately subverted and abused his role as an investigator with the appellant. Mr. Kendal never held an <EM>honest</EM>, albeit mistaken <UNDER>professional</UNDER> belief that reasonable and probable cause did in fact exist: see <EM>Miazga</EM> at para. 79 (underlining added).</P>
<P>95. With respect to the references to the culture within CRA, the trial judge's comments were obiter, and did not form the basis of his findings in respect to Mr. Kendal. However there was ample evidence upon which the trial judge could conclude was indicative of a unfortunate culture within CRA, most notably the conduct of Mr. Kendal and Mr. Alan Jones.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>96. That this appeal be dismissed with costs payable to the respondents.</P>
<P><BOLD>All of which is respectfully submitted.</BOLD></P>
